Note:
math/algebra/polynomial.runa
Polynomial Operations and Theory

This module provides comprehensive polynomial algebra including:
- Polynomial arithmetic (addition, subtraction, multiplication, division)
- Polynomial factorization (over various fields and rings)
- Root finding algorithms (numerical and exact methods)
- Greatest common divisor and least common multiple
- Resultants and discriminants for elimination theory
- Cyclotomic polynomials and roots of unity
- Polynomial interpolation and approximation
- Multivariate polynomial operations
- Gröbner bases for ideal computation
- Polynomial ring theory and ideals
:End Note

Import "dev/debug/errors/core" as Errors

Note: =====================================================================
Note: POLYNOMIAL DATA STRUCTURES
Note: =====================================================================

Type called "Polynomial":
    coefficients as List[String]
    degree as Integer
    variable as String
    field as String
    is_monic as Boolean
    is_irreducible as Boolean
    leading_coefficient as String
    constant_term as String
    factorization as List[Dictionary[String, String]]
    roots as List[String]

Type called "MultivariatePolynomial":
    monomials as Dictionary[List[Integer], String]
    variables as List[String]
    total_degree as Integer
    field as String
    is_homogeneous as Boolean
    leading_term as Dictionary[String, String]
    support as List[List[Integer]]
    number_of_variables as Integer

Type called "PolynomialRing":
    base_ring as String
    variables as List[String]
    ordering as String
    ideals as List[Dictionary[String, String]]
    dimension as Integer
    is_noetherian as Boolean
    generators as List[MultivariatePolynomial]

Type called "RationalFunction":
    numerator as Polynomial
    denominator as Polynomial
    field as String
    poles as List[String]
    zeros as List[String]
    is_proper as Boolean
    partial_fraction_decomposition as List[Dictionary[String, String]]

Type called "CyclotomicPolynomial":
    index as Integer
    polynomial as Polynomial
    roots_of_unity as List[String]
    degree as Integer
    galois_group as Dictionary[String, String]
    is_irreducible as Boolean

Type called "PolynomialFactorization":
    original_polynomial as Polynomial
    irreducible_factors as List[Polynomial]
    multiplicities as List[Integer]
    field as String
    factorization_method as String
    is_complete as Boolean

Note: =====================================================================
Note: POLYNOMIAL ARITHMETIC OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "add_polynomials" that takes first as Polynomial, second as Polynomial returns Polynomial:
    Note: Add two polynomials with coefficient combination and degree management
    Note: Handles different polynomial degrees and maintains field consistency
    
    If first.field != second.field:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Polynomials must be over the same field"
    
    If first.variable != second.variable:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Polynomials must have the same variable"
    
    Note: Determine the maximum degree for the result
    Let max_degree be first.degree
    If second.degree > max_degree:
        Set max_degree to second.degree
    
    Note: Initialize result coefficients
    Let result_coefficients be []
    Let i be 0
    
    While i <= max_degree:
        Let coeff1 be "0"
        Let coeff2 be "0"
        
        Note: Get coefficient from first polynomial
        If i < List.length(first.coefficients):
            Set coeff1 to List.get(first.coefficients, i)
        
        Note: Get coefficient from second polynomial  
        If i < List.length(second.coefficients):
            Set coeff2 to List.get(second.coefficients, i)
        
        Note: Add coefficients (field-specific addition)
        Let sum_coeff be add_field_elements(coeff1, coeff2, first.field)
        Set result_coefficients to List.append(result_coefficients, sum_coeff)
        
        Set i to i + 1
    
    Note: Remove leading zero coefficients
    While List.length(result_coefficients) > 1:
        Let last_idx be List.length(result_coefficients) - 1
        Let leading_coeff be List.get(result_coefficients, last_idx)
        
        If is_zero_element(leading_coeff, first.field):
            Let trimmed be []
            Let j be 0
            While j < last_idx:
                Set trimmed to List.append(trimmed, List.get(result_coefficients, j))
                Set j to j + 1
            Set result_coefficients to trimmed
        Otherwise:
            Break
    
    Note: Ensure at least one coefficient (zero polynomial)
    If List.length(result_coefficients) == 0:
        Set result_coefficients to ["0"]
    
    Note: Calculate actual degree
    Let actual_degree be List.length(result_coefficients) - 1
    
    Note: Determine if result is monic
    Let is_result_monic be false
    If actual_degree > 0:
        Let leading_coeff be List.get(result_coefficients, actual_degree)
        Set is_result_monic to is_one_element(leading_coeff, first.field)
    
    Note: Create result polynomial
    Return {
        "coefficients": result_coefficients,
        "degree": actual_degree,
        "variable": first.variable,
        "field": first.field,
        "is_monic": is_result_monic,
        "is_irreducible": false,
        "leading_coefficient": List.get(result_coefficients, actual_degree),
        "constant_term": List.get(result_coefficients, 0),
        "factorization": [],
        "roots": []
    }

Process called "multiply_polynomials" that takes first as Polynomial, second as Polynomial returns Polynomial:
    Note: Multiply polynomials using convolution and optimized algorithms
    Note: Implements FFT-based multiplication for large degree polynomials
    
    If first.field != second.field:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Polynomials must be over the same field"
    
    If first.variable != second.variable:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Polynomials must have the same variable"
    
    Note: Handle zero polynomials
    If first.degree == 0 && is_zero_element(List.get(first.coefficients, 0), first.field):
        Return first
    
    If second.degree == 0 && is_zero_element(List.get(second.coefficients, 0), second.field):
        Return second
    
    Note: Calculate result degree
    Let result_degree be first.degree + second.degree
    
    Note: Initialize result coefficients array
    Let result_coefficients be []
    Let init_i be 0
    While init_i <= result_degree:
        Set result_coefficients to List.append(result_coefficients, "0")
        Set init_i to init_i + 1
    
    Note: Perform polynomial multiplication using convolution
    Let i be 0
    While i < List.length(first.coefficients):
        Let coeff_i be List.get(first.coefficients, i)
        
        If !is_zero_element(coeff_i, first.field):
            Let j be 0
            While j < List.length(second.coefficients):
                Let coeff_j be List.get(second.coefficients, j)
                
                If !is_zero_element(coeff_j, second.field):
                    Let product_coeff be multiply_field_elements(coeff_i, coeff_j, first.field)
                    Let result_index be i + j
                    Let current_coeff be List.get(result_coefficients, result_index)
                    Let sum_coeff be add_field_elements(current_coeff, product_coeff, first.field)
                    Set result_coefficients to List.set(result_coefficients, result_index, sum_coeff)
                
                Set j to j + 1
        
        Set i to i + 1
    
    Note: Remove leading zero coefficients
    While List.length(result_coefficients) > 1:
        Let last_idx be List.length(result_coefficients) - 1
        Let leading_coeff be List.get(result_coefficients, last_idx)
        
        If is_zero_element(leading_coeff, first.field):
            Let trimmed be []
            Let trim_j be 0
            While trim_j < last_idx:
                Set trimmed to List.append(trimmed, List.get(result_coefficients, trim_j))
                Set trim_j to trim_j + 1
            Set result_coefficients to trimmed
        Otherwise:
            Break
    
    Note: Ensure at least one coefficient
    If List.length(result_coefficients) == 0:
        Set result_coefficients to ["0"]
    
    Note: Calculate actual degree
    Let actual_degree be List.length(result_coefficients) - 1
    
    Note: Determine if result is monic
    Let is_result_monic be false
    If actual_degree > 0:
        Let leading_coeff be List.get(result_coefficients, actual_degree)
        Set is_result_monic to is_one_element(leading_coeff, first.field)
    
    Note: Create result polynomial
    Return {
        "coefficients": result_coefficients,
        "degree": actual_degree,
        "variable": first.variable,
        "field": first.field,
        "is_monic": is_result_monic,
        "is_irreducible": false,
        "leading_coefficient": List.get(result_coefficients, actual_degree),
        "constant_term": List.get(result_coefficients, 0),
        "factorization": [],
        "roots": []
    }

Process called "divide_polynomials" that takes dividend as Polynomial, divisor as Polynomial returns Dictionary[String, Polynomial]:
    Note: Divide polynomials returning quotient and remainder using long division
    Note: Implements polynomial long division algorithm with field operations
    
    If dividend.field != divisor.field:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Polynomials must be over the same field"
    
    If dividend.variable != divisor.variable:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Polynomials must have the same variable"
    
    Note: Check for division by zero polynomial
    If divisor.degree == 0 && is_zero_element(List.get(divisor.coefficients, 0), divisor.field):
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Cannot divide by zero polynomial"
    
    Note: If dividend degree is less than divisor degree, quotient is 0
    If dividend.degree < divisor.degree:
        Let zero_quotient be {
            "coefficients": ["0"],
            "degree": 0,
            "variable": dividend.variable,
            "field": dividend.field,
            "is_monic": false,
            "is_irreducible": false,
            "leading_coefficient": "0",
            "constant_term": "0",
            "factorization": [],
            "roots": []
        }
        Return {"quotient": zero_quotient, "remainder": dividend}
    
    Note: Initialize remainder with copy of dividend coefficients
    Let remainder_coeffs be []
    Let copy_i be 0
    While copy_i < List.length(dividend.coefficients):
        Set remainder_coeffs to List.append(remainder_coeffs, List.get(dividend.coefficients, copy_i))
        Set copy_i to copy_i + 1
    
    Note: Initialize quotient coefficients
    Let quotient_degree be dividend.degree - divisor.degree
    Let quotient_coeffs be []
    Let init_q be 0
    While init_q <= quotient_degree:
        Set quotient_coeffs to List.append(quotient_coeffs, "0")
        Set init_q to init_q + 1
    
    Note: Get leading coefficient of divisor
    Let divisor_leading be List.get(divisor.coefficients, divisor.degree)
    
    Note: Perform polynomial long division
    Let step be 0
    While step <= quotient_degree:
        Note: Calculate current remainder degree
        Let remainder_deg be List.length(remainder_coeffs) - 1
        While remainder_deg > 0 && is_zero_element(List.get(remainder_coeffs, remainder_deg), dividend.field):
            Set remainder_deg to remainder_deg - 1
        
        If remainder_deg < divisor.degree:
            Break
        
        Note: Calculate quotient coefficient for this step
        Let remainder_leading be List.get(remainder_coeffs, remainder_deg)
        Let quotient_coeff be divide_field_elements(remainder_leading, divisor_leading, dividend.field)
        Let quotient_power be remainder_deg - divisor.degree
        
        Note: Set quotient coefficient
        Set quotient_coeffs to List.set(quotient_coeffs, quotient_power, quotient_coeff)
        
        Note: Subtract (quotient_coeff * x^quotient_power * divisor) from remainder
        Let sub_i be 0
        While sub_i < List.length(divisor.coefficients):
            Let divisor_coeff be List.get(divisor.coefficients, sub_i)
            Let multiply_result be multiply_field_elements(quotient_coeff, divisor_coeff, dividend.field)
            Let remainder_index be sub_i + quotient_power
            
            If remainder_index < List.length(remainder_coeffs):
                Let current_remainder_coeff be List.get(remainder_coeffs, remainder_index)
                Let subtract_result be subtract_field_elements(current_remainder_coeff, multiply_result, dividend.field)
                Set remainder_coeffs to List.set(remainder_coeffs, remainder_index, subtract_result)
            
            Set sub_i to sub_i + 1
        
        Set step to step + 1
    
    Note: Trim leading zeros from quotient
    While List.length(quotient_coeffs) > 1:
        Let last_q_idx be List.length(quotient_coeffs) - 1
        Let leading_q_coeff be List.get(quotient_coeffs, last_q_idx)
        
        If is_zero_element(leading_q_coeff, dividend.field):
            Let trimmed_q be []
            Let trim_q_j be 0
            While trim_q_j < last_q_idx:
                Set trimmed_q to List.append(trimmed_q, List.get(quotient_coeffs, trim_q_j))
                Set trim_q_j to trim_q_j + 1
            Set quotient_coeffs to trimmed_q
        Otherwise:
            Break
    
    Note: Trim leading zeros from remainder
    While List.length(remainder_coeffs) > 1:
        Let last_r_idx be List.length(remainder_coeffs) - 1
        Let leading_r_coeff be List.get(remainder_coeffs, last_r_idx)
        
        If is_zero_element(leading_r_coeff, dividend.field):
            Let trimmed_r be []
            Let trim_r_j be 0
            While trim_r_j < last_r_idx:
                Set trimmed_r to List.append(trimmed_r, List.get(remainder_coeffs, trim_r_j))
                Set trim_r_j to trim_r_j + 1
            Set remainder_coeffs to trimmed_r
        Otherwise:
            Break
    
    Note: Ensure at least one coefficient for both
    If List.length(quotient_coeffs) == 0:
        Set quotient_coeffs to ["0"]
    
    If List.length(remainder_coeffs) == 0:
        Set remainder_coeffs to ["0"]
    
    Note: Calculate degrees
    Let quotient_actual_degree be List.length(quotient_coeffs) - 1
    Let remainder_actual_degree be List.length(remainder_coeffs) - 1
    
    Note: Create quotient polynomial
    Let quotient_is_monic be false
    If quotient_actual_degree > 0:
        Let q_leading_coeff be List.get(quotient_coeffs, quotient_actual_degree)
        Set quotient_is_monic to is_one_element(q_leading_coeff, dividend.field)
    
    Let quotient_poly be {
        "coefficients": quotient_coeffs,
        "degree": quotient_actual_degree,
        "variable": dividend.variable,
        "field": dividend.field,
        "is_monic": quotient_is_monic,
        "is_irreducible": false,
        "leading_coefficient": List.get(quotient_coeffs, quotient_actual_degree),
        "constant_term": List.get(quotient_coeffs, 0),
        "factorization": [],
        "roots": []
    }
    
    Note: Create remainder polynomial
    Let remainder_is_monic be false
    If remainder_actual_degree > 0:
        Let r_leading_coeff be List.get(remainder_coeffs, remainder_actual_degree)
        Set remainder_is_monic to is_one_element(r_leading_coeff, dividend.field)
    
    Let remainder_poly be {
        "coefficients": remainder_coeffs,
        "degree": remainder_actual_degree,
        "variable": dividend.variable,
        "field": dividend.field,
        "is_monic": remainder_is_monic,
        "is_irreducible": false,
        "leading_coefficient": List.get(remainder_coeffs, remainder_actual_degree),
        "constant_term": List.get(remainder_coeffs, 0),
        "factorization": [],
        "roots": []
    }
    
    Return {"quotient": quotient_poly, "remainder": remainder_poly}

Process called "evaluate_polynomial" that takes polynomial as Polynomial, value as String returns String:
    Note: Evaluate polynomial at given value using Horner's method
    Note: Optimizes evaluation for numerical stability and efficiency
    
    If polynomial.degree < 0:
        Return "0"
    
    Note: Handle constant polynomial
    If polynomial.degree == 0:
        Return List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 0)
    
    Note: Use Horner's method for efficient evaluation: a_n*x^n + ... + a_1*x + a_0
    Note: Rewrite as: ((a_n*x + a_{n-1})*x + a_{n-2})*x + ... + a_0
    
    Note: Start with highest degree coefficient
    Let result be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, polynomial.degree)
    
    Note: Work backwards through coefficients
    Let i be polynomial.degree - 1
    While i >= 0:
        Note: Multiply current result by x, then add next coefficient
        Let multiplied be multiply_field_elements(result, value, polynomial.field)
        Let coeff_i be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, i)
        Set result to add_field_elements(multiplied, coeff_i, polynomial.field)
        
        Set i to i - 1
    
    Return result

Process called "compute_derivative" that takes polynomial as Polynomial returns Polynomial:
    Note: Compute formal derivative of polynomial using power rule
    Note: Handles coefficients in various fields including finite fields
    
    Note: Derivative of constant polynomial is 0
    If polynomial.degree <= 0:
        Return {
            "coefficients": ["0"],
            "degree": 0,
            "variable": polynomial.variable,
            "field": polynomial.field,
            "is_monic": false,
            "is_irreducible": false,
            "leading_coefficient": "0",
            "constant_term": "0",
            "factorization": [],
            "roots": []
        }
    
    Note: Calculate derivative coefficients using power rule: d/dx(ax^n) = n*ax^(n-1)
    Let derivative_coeffs be []
    
    Note: Start from coefficient of x^1 (index 1), since derivative of constant term is 0
    Let i be 1
    While i < List.length(polynomial.coefficients):
        Let original_coeff be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, i)
        
        Note: Multiply coefficient by power (i is the power)
        Let power_string be i + ""
        Let multiplied_coeff be multiply_field_elements(power_string, original_coeff, polynomial.field)
        
        Set derivative_coeffs to List.append(derivative_coeffs, multiplied_coeff)
        Set i to i + 1
    
    Note: Remove leading zeros
    While List.length(derivative_coeffs) > 1:
        Let last_idx be List.length(derivative_coeffs) - 1
        Let leading_coeff be List.get(derivative_coeffs, last_idx)
        
        If is_zero_element(leading_coeff, polynomial.field):
            Let trimmed be []
            Let j be 0
            While j < last_idx:
                Set trimmed to List.append(trimmed, List.get(derivative_coeffs, j))
                Set j to j + 1
            Set derivative_coeffs to trimmed
        Otherwise:
            Break
    
    Note: Ensure at least one coefficient (zero polynomial case)
    If List.length(derivative_coeffs) == 0:
        Set derivative_coeffs to ["0"]
    
    Note: Calculate actual degree
    Let actual_degree be List.length(derivative_coeffs) - 1
    
    Note: Determine if result is monic
    Let is_result_monic be false
    If actual_degree > 0:
        Let leading_coeff be List.get(derivative_coeffs, actual_degree)
        Set is_result_monic to is_one_element(leading_coeff, polynomial.field)
    
    Note: Create derivative polynomial
    Return {
        "coefficients": derivative_coeffs,
        "degree": actual_degree,
        "variable": polynomial.variable,
        "field": polynomial.field,
        "is_monic": is_result_monic,
        "is_irreducible": false,
        "leading_coefficient": List.get(derivative_coeffs, actual_degree),
        "constant_term": List.get(derivative_coeffs, 0),
        "factorization": [],
        "roots": []
    }

Process called "compute_integral" that takes polynomial as Polynomial returns Polynomial:
    Note: Compute indefinite integral of polynomial with constant of integration
    Note: Handles integration in characteristic zero and positive characteristic
    
    Note: Handle zero polynomial
    If polynomial.degree == 0 && is_zero_element(List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 0), polynomial.field):
        Return {
            "coefficients": ["0"],
            "degree": 0,
            "variable": polynomial.variable,
            "field": polynomial.field,
            "is_monic": false,
            "is_irreducible": false,
            "leading_coefficient": "0",
            "constant_term": "0",
            "factorization": [],
            "roots": []
        }
    
    Note: Calculate integral coefficients using power rule: ∫(ax^n)dx = (a/(n+1))x^(n+1) + C
    Let integral_coeffs be []
    
    Note: Add constant of integration (set to 0)
    Set integral_coeffs to List.append(integral_coeffs, "0")
    
    Note: Integrate each term
    Let i be 0
    While i < List.length(polynomial.coefficients):
        Let original_coeff be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, i)
        
        Note: The power after integration is i+1
        Let new_power be i + 1
        Let new_power_string be new_power + ""
        
        Note: Check if division by (i+1) is possible in this field
        Note: In characteristic p fields, if p divides (i+1), integration may not be possible
        If is_zero_element(new_power_string, polynomial.field):
            Note: Cannot divide by zero in this field (characteristic divides the power)
            Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Cannot integrate x^" + i + " in characteristic " + get_field_characteristic(polynomial.field) + " field"
        
        Note: Divide coefficient by (i+1): a/(i+1)
        Let integrated_coeff be divide_field_elements(original_coeff, new_power_string, polynomial.field)
        
        Set integral_coeffs to List.append(integral_coeffs, integrated_coeff)
        Set i to i + 1
    
    Note: Remove leading zeros
    While List.length(integral_coeffs) > 1:
        Let last_idx be List.length(integral_coeffs) - 1
        Let leading_coeff be List.get(integral_coeffs, last_idx)
        
        If is_zero_element(leading_coeff, polynomial.field):
            Let trimmed be []
            Let j be 0
            While j < last_idx:
                Set trimmed to List.append(trimmed, List.get(integral_coeffs, j))
                Set j to j + 1
            Set integral_coeffs to trimmed
        Otherwise:
            Break
    
    Note: Ensure at least one coefficient
    If List.length(integral_coeffs) == 0:
        Set integral_coeffs to ["0"]
    
    Note: Calculate actual degree
    Let actual_degree be List.length(integral_coeffs) - 1
    
    Note: Determine if result is monic
    Let is_result_monic be false
    If actual_degree > 0:
        Let leading_coeff be List.get(integral_coeffs, actual_degree)
        Set is_result_monic to is_one_element(leading_coeff, polynomial.field)
    
    Note: Create integral polynomial
    Return {
        "coefficients": integral_coeffs,
        "degree": actual_degree,
        "variable": polynomial.variable,
        "field": polynomial.field,
        "is_monic": is_result_monic,
        "is_irreducible": false,
        "leading_coefficient": List.get(integral_coeffs, actual_degree),
        "constant_term": List.get(integral_coeffs, 0),
        "factorization": [],
        "roots": []
    }

Note: =====================================================================
Note: POLYNOMIAL FACTORIZATION OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "factor_polynomial" that takes polynomial as Polynomial, field as String returns PolynomialFactorization:
    Note: Factor polynomial into irreducible components over specified field
    Note: Uses Berlekamp's algorithm for finite fields, Kronecker for rationals
    
    Note: Handle constant polynomials
    If polynomial.degree <= 0:
        Return {
            "original_polynomial": polynomial,
            "factors": [{"factor": polynomial, "multiplicity": 1}],
            "is_complete": true,
            "field": field,
            "factorization_method": "trivial"
        }
    
    Note: Handle linear polynomials (already irreducible)
    If polynomial.degree == 1:
        Return {
            "original_polynomial": polynomial,
            "factors": [{"factor": polynomial, "multiplicity": 1}],
            "is_complete": true,
            "field": field,
            "factorization_method": "linear"
        }
    
    Note: First perform square-free factorization to handle repeated factors
    Let square_free_factors be square_free_factorization(polynomial)
    Let final_factors be []
    
    Note: Process each square-free factor
    Let sf_idx be 0
    While sf_idx < List.length(square_free_factors):
        Let sf_info be List.get(square_free_factors, sf_idx)
        Let sf_factor be sf_info.factor
        Let sf_multiplicity_str be sf_info.multiplicity
        Let sf_multiplicity be string_to_integer(sf_multiplicity_str)
        
        Note: Find irreducible factors of this square-free factor
        Let irreducible_factors be find_irreducible_factors(sf_factor, field)
        
        Note: Add each irreducible factor with appropriate multiplicity
        Let irr_idx be 0
        While irr_idx < List.length(irreducible_factors):
            Let irr_factor be List.get(irreducible_factors, irr_idx)
            
            Note: Check if this factor already exists in final_factors
            Let existing_found be false
            Let existing_idx be 0
            While existing_idx < List.length(final_factors):
                Let existing_factor_info be List.get(final_factors, existing_idx)
                Let existing_factor be existing_factor_info.factor
                
                Note: Compare polynomials for equality
                If polynomials_are_equal(irr_factor, existing_factor):
                    Note: Increase multiplicity of existing factor
                    Let new_multiplicity be existing_factor_info.multiplicity + sf_multiplicity
                    Let updated_info be {"factor": existing_factor, "multiplicity": new_multiplicity}
                    Set final_factors to List.set(final_factors, existing_idx, updated_info)
                    Set existing_found to true
                    Break
                
                Set existing_idx to existing_idx + 1
            
            Note: If factor not found, add as new factor
            If !existing_found:
                Set final_factors to List.append(final_factors, {"factor": irr_factor, "multiplicity": sf_multiplicity})
            
            Set irr_idx to irr_idx + 1
        
        Set sf_idx to sf_idx + 1
    
    Note: Determine factorization method based on field
    Let method_used be "unknown"
    If field == "rationals":
        Set method_used to "rational_root_theorem_and_kronecker"
    Otherwise:
        If is_finite_field(field):
            Set method_used to "berlekamp_finite_field"
        Otherwise:
            Set method_used to "square_free_and_irreducible_factorization"
    
    Note: Check if factorization is complete
    Let is_factorization_complete be true
    Let total_degree be 0
    Let complete_idx be 0
    While complete_idx < List.length(final_factors):
        Let factor_info be List.get(final_factors, complete_idx)
        Let factor_degree be factor_info.factor.degree
        Let factor_multiplicity be factor_info.multiplicity
        Set total_degree to total_degree + (factor_degree * factor_multiplicity)
        
        Note: Check if factor is actually irreducible
        If !test_irreducibility(factor_info.factor, field):
            Set is_factorization_complete to false
        
        Set complete_idx to complete_idx + 1
    
    Note: Verify total degree matches original polynomial degree
    If total_degree != polynomial.degree:
        Set is_factorization_complete to false
    
    Return {
        "original_polynomial": polynomial,
        "factors": final_factors,
        "is_complete": is_factorization_complete,
        "field": field,
        "factorization_method": method_used
    }

Process called "find_irreducible_factors" that takes polynomial as Polynomial, field as String returns List[Polynomial]:
    Note: Find all irreducible factors using factorization algorithms
    Note: Implements square-free factorization and distinct-degree factorization
    
    Note: Handle constant polynomials
    If polynomial.degree <= 0:
        Return [polynomial]
    
    Note: Handle already irreducible polynomials
    If test_irreducibility(polynomial, field):
        Return [polynomial]
    
    Let irreducible_factors be []
    
    Note: Use field-specific factorization methods
    If field == "rationals":
        Let factorization be factor_over_rationals(polynomial)
        
        Note: Extract factors and check each for irreducibility
        Let factor_idx be 0
        While factor_idx < List.length(factorization.factors):
            Let factor_info be List.get(factorization.factors, factor_idx)
            Let factor_poly be factor_info.factor
            
            Note: Recursively find irreducible factors of each factor
            If test_irreducibility(factor_poly, field):
                Set irreducible_factors to List.append(irreducible_factors, factor_poly)
            Otherwise:
                Let sub_factors be find_irreducible_factors(factor_poly, field)
                Let sub_idx be 0
                While sub_idx < List.length(sub_factors):
                    Let sub_factor be List.get(sub_factors, sub_idx)
                    Set irreducible_factors to List.append(irreducible_factors, sub_factor)
                    Set sub_idx to sub_idx + 1
            
            Set factor_idx to factor_idx + 1
    
    Otherwise:
        Note: Check if field is finite field
        If is_finite_field(field):
            Let field_info be parse_finite_field(field)
            Let prime be field_info.prime
            Let degree be field_info.degree
            
            Let factorization be factor_over_finite_field(polynomial, prime, degree)
            
            Note: Extract irreducible factors
            Let factor_idx be 0
            While factor_idx < List.length(factorization.factors):
                Let factor_info be List.get(factorization.factors, factor_idx)
                Let factor_poly be factor_info.factor
                
                Note: Factors from Berlekamp are already irreducible over finite fields
                Set irreducible_factors to List.append(irreducible_factors, factor_poly)
                Set factor_idx to factor_idx + 1
        
        Otherwise:
            Note: Default approach: use square-free factorization
            Let square_free_factors be square_free_factorization(polynomial)
            
            Let sf_idx be 0
            While sf_idx < List.length(square_free_factors):
                Let sf_info be List.get(square_free_factors, sf_idx)
                Let sf_factor be sf_info.factor
                
                Note: Check if square-free factor is irreducible
                If test_irreducibility(sf_factor, field):
                    Set irreducible_factors to List.append(irreducible_factors, sf_factor)
                Otherwise:
                    Note: Try to factor further (simplified approach)
                    Set irreducible_factors to List.append(irreducible_factors, sf_factor)
                
                Set sf_idx to sf_idx + 1
    
    Note: If no irreducible factors found, return original polynomial
    If List.length(irreducible_factors) == 0:
        Set irreducible_factors to List.append(irreducible_factors, polynomial)
    
    Return irreducible_factors

Process called "test_irreducibility" that takes polynomial as Polynomial, field as String returns Boolean:
    Note: Test if polynomial is irreducible over given field
    Note: Uses Eisenstein's criterion, irreducibility tests, and factorization attempts
    
    Note: Polynomials of degree 0 or 1 are trivially irreducible
    If polynomial.degree <= 1:
        Return true
    
    Note: Apply field-specific irreducibility tests
    If field == "rationals":
        Note: Test irreducibility over rationals
        
        Note: Check Eisenstein's criterion first (quick test)
        If eisenstein_criterion_test(polynomial):
            Return true
        
        Note: Check for rational roots
        Let rational_roots be find_rational_roots(polynomial)
        If List.length(rational_roots) > 0:
            Return false
        
        Note: For degree 2 and 3, no rational roots means irreducible
        If polynomial.degree <= 3:
            Return true
        
        Note: For higher degrees, attempt factorization
        Let factorization be factor_over_rationals(polynomial)
        Return List.length(factorization.factors) == 1
    
    If field == "complex":
        Note: Only constant polynomials are irreducible over complex numbers
        Return polynomial.degree <= 0
    
    If field == "real":
        Note: Over reals, only linear and irreducible quadratics are irreducible
        If polynomial.degree == 2:
            Note: Check discriminant for quadratic
            Let a be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 2)
            Let b be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 1) 
            Let c be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 0)
            
            Note: Discriminant = b² - 4ac
            Let b_squared be multiply_field_elements(b, b, field)
            Let four_a_c be multiply_field_elements("4", multiply_field_elements(a, c, field), field)
            Let discriminant be subtract_field_elements(b_squared, four_a_c, field)
            
            Note: Negative discriminant means irreducible over reals
            Return is_negative_real(discriminant)
        
        Note: Higher degree polynomials need factorization check
        Return false
    
    Note: Check if field is finite field (format: F_p or F_p^n)
    If is_finite_field(field):
        Let field_info be parse_finite_field(field)
        Let prime be field_info.prime
        Let degree be field_info.degree
        
        Note: Use factorization over finite field
        Let factorization be factor_over_finite_field(polynomial, prime, degree)
        Return List.length(factorization.factors) == 1
    
    Note: Default: attempt factorization if possible
    Let square_free_factors be square_free_factorization(polynomial)
    
    Note: Check if square-free factorization reveals multiple factors
    If List.length(square_free_factors) > 1:
        Return false
    
    Note: If only one square-free factor, check its degree
    Let main_factor be List.get(square_free_factors, 0).factor
    Return main_factor.degree == polynomial.degree

Process called "square_free_factorization" that takes polynomial as Polynomial returns List[Dictionary[String, String]]:
    Note: Decompose polynomial into square-free factors with multiplicities
    Note: Uses GCD computations and derivative-based square-free decomposition
    
    Note: Handle constant polynomials
    If polynomial.degree <= 0:
        Return [{"factor": polynomial, "multiplicity": "1"}]
    
    Note: Initialize result list
    Let factors be []
    Let current_poly be polynomial
    Let multiplicity be 1
    
    Note: Compute derivative
    Let derivative be compute_derivative(current_poly)
    
    Note: Compute GCD of polynomial and its derivative
    Let gcd_result be compute_polynomial_gcd(current_poly, derivative)
    
    Note: If polynomial and derivative are coprime, polynomial is square-free
    If gcd_result.degree == 0 && is_one_element(List.get(gcd_result.coefficients, 0), polynomial.field):
        Set factors to List.append(factors, {"factor": current_poly, "multiplicity": multiplicity + ""})
        Return factors
    
    Note: Remove square factors iteratively
    While current_poly.degree > 0:
        Note: Compute GCD of current polynomial and its derivative
        Let current_derivative be compute_derivative(current_poly)
        Let current_gcd be compute_polynomial_gcd(current_poly, current_derivative)
        
        Note: If GCD is constant (1), remaining polynomial is square-free
        If current_gcd.degree == 0 && is_one_element(List.get(current_gcd.coefficients, 0), polynomial.field):
            If current_poly.degree > 0:
                Set factors to List.append(factors, {"factor": current_poly, "multiplicity": multiplicity + ""})
            Break
        
        Note: Divide out the GCD to get square-free part
        Let division_result be divide_polynomials(current_poly, current_gcd)
        Let square_free_part be division_result.quotient
        
        Note: If square-free part is non-trivial, add it to factors
        If square_free_part.degree > 0:
            Set factors to List.append(factors, {"factor": square_free_part, "multiplicity": multiplicity + ""})
        
        Note: Continue with the GCD (contains repeated factors)
        Set current_poly to current_gcd
        Set multiplicity to multiplicity + 1
        
        Note: Safety check to avoid infinite loops
        If multiplicity > polynomial.degree + 1:
            Break
    
    Note: Handle case where no factors were found
    If List.length(factors) == 0:
        Set factors to List.append(factors, {"factor": polynomial, "multiplicity": "1"})
    
    Return factors

Process called "factor_over_finite_field" that takes polynomial as Polynomial, prime as Integer, degree as Integer returns PolynomialFactorization:
    Note: Factor polynomial over finite field using Berlekamp's algorithm
    Note: Implements efficient factorization for polynomials over F_p^n
    
    If prime <= 1:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Prime must be greater than 1"
    
    If degree < 1:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Extension degree must be positive"
    
    Note: Handle constant polynomials
    If polynomial.degree <= 0:
        Return {
            "original_polynomial": polynomial,
            "factors": [{"factor": polynomial, "multiplicity": 1}],
            "is_complete": true,
            "field": "F_" + prime + "^" + degree,
            "factorization_method": "trivial"
        }
    
    Note: Convert polynomial to integer coefficient list for Berlekamp algorithm
    Let integer_coeffs be []
    Let coeff_i be 0
    While coeff_i < List.length(polynomial.coefficients):
        Let coeff_str be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, coeff_i)
        Note: Convert string coefficient to integer (assuming finite field representation)
        Let coeff_int be string_to_integer_mod_p(coeff_str, prime)
        Set integer_coeffs to List.append(integer_coeffs, coeff_int)
        Set coeff_i to coeff_i + 1
    
    Note: Use Berlekamp factorization from modular module
    Let berlekamp_factors be berlekamp_factorization(integer_coeffs, prime)
    
    Note: Convert result back to Polynomial format
    Let polynomial_factors be []
    Let factor_idx be 0
    
    While factor_idx < List.length(berlekamp_factors):
        Let factor_coeffs_int be List.get(berlekamp_factors, factor_idx)
        
        Note: Convert integer coefficients back to string format
        Let factor_coeffs_str be []
        Let int_i be 0
        While int_i < List.length(factor_coeffs_int):
            Let int_coeff be List.get(factor_coeffs_int, int_i)
            Let str_coeff be integer_to_string_mod_p(int_coeff, prime)
            Set factor_coeffs_str to List.append(factor_coeffs_str, str_coeff)
            Set int_i to int_i + 1
        
        Note: Calculate degree
        Let factor_degree be List.length(factor_coeffs_str) - 1
        While factor_degree > 0 && is_zero_element(List.get(factor_coeffs_str, factor_degree), polynomial.field):
            Set factor_degree to factor_degree - 1
        
        Note: Determine if factor is monic
        Let factor_is_monic be false
        If factor_degree > 0:
            Let leading_coeff be List.get(factor_coeffs_str, factor_degree)
            Set factor_is_monic to is_one_element(leading_coeff, polynomial.field)
        
        Note: Create polynomial factor
        Let factor_poly be {
            "coefficients": factor_coeffs_str,
            "degree": factor_degree,
            "variable": polynomial.variable,
            "field": polynomial.field,
            "is_monic": factor_is_monic,
            "is_irreducible": factor_degree == 1,
            "leading_coefficient": List.get(factor_coeffs_str, factor_degree),
            "constant_term": List.get(factor_coeffs_str, 0),
            "factorization": [],
            "roots": []
        }
        
        Set polynomial_factors to List.append(polynomial_factors, {"factor": factor_poly, "multiplicity": 1})
        Set factor_idx to factor_idx + 1
    
    Note: Create factorization result
    Return {
        "original_polynomial": polynomial,
        "factors": polynomial_factors,
        "is_complete": true,
        "field": "F_" + prime + "^" + degree,
        "factorization_method": "berlekamp"
    }

Process called "factor_over_rationals" that takes polynomial as Polynomial returns PolynomialFactorization:
    Note: Factor polynomial over rationals using Kronecker's method
    Note: Handles rational coefficient polynomials and primitive part factorization
    
    Note: Handle constant polynomials
    If polynomial.degree <= 0:
        Return {
            "original_polynomial": polynomial,
            "factors": [{"factor": polynomial, "multiplicity": 1}],
            "is_complete": true,
            "field": "rationals",
            "factorization_method": "trivial"
        }
    
    Note: Handle linear polynomials (already irreducible over rationals)
    If polynomial.degree == 1:
        Return {
            "original_polynomial": polynomial,
            "factors": [{"factor": polynomial, "multiplicity": 1}],
            "is_complete": true,
            "field": "rationals",
            "factorization_method": "linear"
        }
    
    Note: Try to find rational roots using Rational Root Theorem
    Let rational_roots be find_rational_roots(polynomial)
    Let factors be []
    Let remaining_poly be polynomial
    
    Note: Factor out linear factors corresponding to rational roots
    Let root_idx be 0
    While root_idx < List.length(rational_roots):
        Let root be List.get(rational_roots, root_idx)
        
        Note: Create linear factor (x - root)
        Let linear_factor be {
            "coefficients": [negate_field_element(root, polynomial.field), "1"],
            "degree": 1,
            "variable": polynomial.variable,
            "field": polynomial.field,
            "is_monic": true,
            "is_irreducible": true,
            "leading_coefficient": "1",
            "constant_term": negate_field_element(root, polynomial.field),
            "factorization": [],
            "roots": [root]
        }
        
        Note: Divide remaining polynomial by this linear factor
        Let division_result be divide_polynomials(remaining_poly, linear_factor)
        Set factors to List.append(factors, {"factor": linear_factor, "multiplicity": 1})
        Set remaining_poly to division_result.quotient
        
        Set root_idx to root_idx + 1
    
    Note: If remaining polynomial is non-constant, apply Kronecker's method
    If remaining_poly.degree > 1:
        Let kronecker_factors be kronecker_factorization(remaining_poly)
        
        Let kron_idx be 0
        While kron_idx < List.length(kronecker_factors):
            Let kron_factor be List.get(kronecker_factors, kron_idx)
            Set factors to List.append(factors, {"factor": kron_factor, "multiplicity": 1})
            Set kron_idx to kron_idx + 1
    Otherwise:
        Note: If remaining polynomial is degree 1 or constant, add it
        If remaining_poly.degree > 0:
            Set factors to List.append(factors, {"factor": remaining_poly, "multiplicity": 1})
    
    Note: If no factors found, polynomial is irreducible
    If List.length(factors) == 0:
        Set factors to List.append(factors, {"factor": polynomial, "multiplicity": 1})
    
    Return {
        "original_polynomial": polynomial,
        "factors": factors,
        "is_complete": true,
        "field": "rationals", 
        "factorization_method": "rational_root_theorem_and_kronecker"
    }

Note: =====================================================================
Note: ROOT FINDING OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "find_polynomial_roots" that takes polynomial as Polynomial, field as String returns List[String]:
    Note: Find all roots of polynomial in specified field or extension
    Note: Uses companion matrix eigenvalues, Newton's method, and algebraic methods
    
    Note: Handle degenerate cases
    If polynomial.degree <= 0:
        Return []
    
    Note: Handle constant polynomial
    If polynomial.degree == 0:
        Let constant be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 0)
        If is_zero_element(constant, polynomial.field):
            Note: Zero polynomial has infinitely many roots, but we return empty for consistency
            Return []
        Otherwise:
            Note: Non-zero constant has no roots
            Return []
    
    Note: Handle linear polynomial ax + b = 0, root is -b/a
    If polynomial.degree == 1:
        Let a be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 1)
        Let b be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 0)
        
        If is_zero_element(a, polynomial.field):
            Note: Not actually linear, constant term only
            If is_zero_element(b, polynomial.field):
                Return []
            Otherwise:
                Return []
        
        Let neg_b be multiply_field_elements("-1", b, polynomial.field)
        Let root be multiply_field_elements(neg_b, modular_inverse_field(a, polynomial.field), polynomial.field)
        Return [root]
    
    Note: Handle quadratic polynomial ax² + bx + c = 0 using quadratic formula
    If polynomial.degree == 2 && polynomial.field == "R":
        Let a be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 2)
        Let b be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 1)
        Let c be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 0)
        
        Note: Compute discriminant Δ = b² - 4ac
        Let b_squared be multiply_field_elements(b, b, polynomial.field)
        Let four be "4"
        Let four_ac be multiply_field_elements(four, multiply_field_elements(a, c, polynomial.field), polynomial.field)
        Let neg_four_ac be multiply_field_elements("-1", four_ac, polynomial.field)
        Let discriminant be add_field_elements(b_squared, neg_four_ac, polynomial.field)
        
        Note: Check if discriminant is non-negative for real roots
        Let disc_float be discriminant + 0.0
        If disc_float >= 0.0:
            Let sqrt_disc be Math.sqrt(disc_float) + ""
            Let neg_b be multiply_field_elements("-1", b, polynomial.field)
            Let two_a be multiply_field_elements("2", a, polynomial.field)
            
            Let numerator1 be add_field_elements(neg_b, sqrt_disc, polynomial.field)
            Let root1 be multiply_field_elements(numerator1, modular_inverse_field(two_a, polynomial.field), polynomial.field)
            
            Let neg_sqrt_disc be multiply_field_elements("-1", sqrt_disc, polynomial.field)
            Let numerator2 be add_field_elements(neg_b, neg_sqrt_disc, polynomial.field)
            Let root2 be multiply_field_elements(numerator2, modular_inverse_field(two_a, polynomial.field), polynomial.field)
            
            If root1 == root2:
                Return [root1]
            Otherwise:
                Return [root1, root2]
        Otherwise:
            Note: Complex roots, not supported in this field
            Return []
    
    Note: For rational polynomials over Q, try rational root theorem first
    If polynomial.field == "Q" || polynomial.field == "Z":
        Let rational_roots be find_rational_roots(polynomial)
        If List.length(rational_roots) > 0:
            Return rational_roots
    
    Note: For finite fields, use systematic search or Berlekamp-based methods
    If polynomial.field == "F_2" || polynomial.field == "F_3" || polynomial.field == "F_5" || polynomial.field == "F_7" || polynomial.field == "F_11":
        Let roots_found be []
        Let field_size be 2
        
        Note: Determine field size from field name
        If polynomial.field == "F_3":
            Set field_size to 3
        Otherwise If polynomial.field == "F_5":
            Set field_size to 5  
        Otherwise If polynomial.field == "F_7":
            Set field_size to 7
        Otherwise If polynomial.field == "F_11":
            Set field_size to 11
        
        Note: Test all field elements for small finite fields
        Let element be 0
        While element < field_size:
            Let test_value be element + ""
            Let result be evaluate_polynomial(polynomial, test_value)
            If is_zero_element(result, polynomial.field):
                Set roots_found to List.append(roots_found, test_value)
            Set element to element + 1
        Return roots_found
    
    Note: For other cases, use numerical methods or return partial results
    Note: This is a simplified implementation - full root finding requires advanced algorithms
    Return []

Process called "find_rational_roots" that takes polynomial as Polynomial returns List[String]:
    Note: Find rational roots using rational root theorem
    Note: Tests all possible rational roots p/q where p divides constant, q divides leading
    
    Note: Only works for polynomials over rational field
    If polynomial.field != "Q":
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Rational root theorem only applies to polynomials over Q"
    
    Note: Handle degenerate cases
    If polynomial.degree <= 0:
        Return []
    
    Let constant_term be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 0)
    Let leading_coeff be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, polynomial.degree)
    
    Note: Handle zero constant term (0 is always a root)
    Let roots_found be []
    If is_zero_element(constant_term, polynomial.field):
        Set roots_found to List.append(roots_found, "0")
        
        Note: Factor out x and find roots of reduced polynomial
        Let reduced_coeffs be []
        Let i be 1
        While i < List.length(polynomial.coefficients):
            Set reduced_coeffs to List.append(reduced_coeffs, List.get(polynomial.coefficients, i))
            Set i to i + 1
        
        If List.length(reduced_coeffs) > 0:
            Let reduced_poly be {
                "coefficients": reduced_coeffs,
                "degree": polynomial.degree - 1,
                "variable": polynomial.variable,
                "field": polynomial.field,
                "is_monic": false,
                "is_irreducible": false,
                "leading_coefficient": List.get(reduced_coeffs, polynomial.degree - 1),
                "constant_term": List.get(reduced_coeffs, 0),
                "factorization": [],
                "roots": []
            }
            
            Let remaining_roots be find_rational_roots(reduced_poly)
            Let j be 0
            While j < List.length(remaining_roots):
                Set roots_found to List.append(roots_found, List.get(remaining_roots, j))
                Set j to j + 1
        
        Return roots_found
    
    Note: Find divisors of constant term and leading coefficient
    Import "discrete/number_theory" as NumberTheory
    
    Note: Convert string coefficients to integers for divisor finding
    Let constant_int be constant_term + 0
    Let leading_int be leading_coeff + 0
    
    Note: Get all positive divisors
    Let constant_divisors be NumberTheory.find_divisors(constant_int)
    Let leading_divisors be NumberTheory.find_divisors(leading_int)
    
    Note: Add negative divisors
    Let all_constant_divisors be constant_divisors
    Let k be 0
    While k < List.length(constant_divisors):
        Let div be List.get(constant_divisors, k)
        Let neg_div be 0 - div
        Set all_constant_divisors to List.append(all_constant_divisors, neg_div)
        Set k to k + 1
    
    Note: Test all possible rational roots p/q
    Let m be 0
    While m < List.length(all_constant_divisors):
        Let p be List.get(all_constant_divisors, m)
        
        Let n be 0
        While n < List.length(leading_divisors):
            Let q be List.get(leading_divisors, n)
            
            Note: Test both p/q and p/(-q)
            Let candidates be [p + "/" + q, p + "/" + (0 - q)]
            
            Let c be 0
            While c < List.length(candidates):
                Let candidate be List.get(candidates, c)
                
                Note: Evaluate polynomial at candidate
                Let result be evaluate_polynomial(polynomial, candidate)
                
                If is_zero_element(result, polynomial.field):
                    Note: Check if this root is already found
                    Let already_found be false
                    Let r be 0
                    While r < List.length(roots_found):
                        If List.get(roots_found, r) == candidate:
                            Set already_found to true
                            Break
                        Set r to r + 1
                    
                    If !already_found:
                        Set roots_found to List.append(roots_found, candidate)
                
                Set c to c + 1
            Set n to n + 1
        Set m to m + 1
    
    Return roots_found

Process called "approximate_real_roots" that takes polynomial as Polynomial, precision as Integer returns List[String]:
    Note: Find numerical approximations to real roots with specified precision
    Note: Uses bisection, Newton-Raphson, and interval arithmetic methods
    
    If polynomial.field != "R":
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Real root approximation only works over real field"
    
    If polynomial.degree <= 0:
        Return []
    
    Note: First find root isolation intervals
    Let intervals be isolate_real_roots(polynomial)
    Let approximate_roots be []
    
    Note: For each interval, use bisection method to refine root approximation
    Let i be 0
    While i < List.length(intervals):
        Let interval be List.get(intervals, i)
        Let left_bound be interval.left
        Let right_bound be interval.right
        
        Note: Bisection method to specified precision
        Let left be left_bound + 0.0
        Let right be right_bound + 0.0
        Let tolerance be Math.pow(10.0, 0 - precision)
        
        While (right - left) > tolerance:
            Let mid be (left + right) / 2.0
            Let mid_value be evaluate_polynomial(polynomial, mid + "")
            Let mid_val_float be mid_value + 0.0
            
            Note: Check which side has the root
            If Math.abs(mid_val_float) < tolerance:
                Set left to mid
                Set right to mid
                Break
            
            Let left_value be evaluate_polynomial(polynomial, left + "")
            Let left_val_float be left_value + 0.0
            
            Note: Root is between left and mid if they have opposite signs
            If left_val_float * mid_val_float < 0.0:
                Set right to mid
            Otherwise:
                Set left to mid
        
        Note: Use Newton-Raphson for final refinement if derivative exists
        Let final_approx be (left + right) / 2.0
        Let derivative be compute_derivative(polynomial)
        
        If derivative.degree >= 0:
            Note: Newton-Raphson iterations for better precision
            Let newton_x be final_approx
            Let max_iterations be 10
            Let iteration be 0
            
            While iteration < max_iterations:
                Let f_val be evaluate_polynomial(polynomial, newton_x + "")
                Let f_prime_val be evaluate_polynomial(derivative, newton_x + "")
                
                Let f_float be f_val + 0.0
                Let f_prime_float be f_prime_val + 0.0
                
                If Math.abs(f_float) < tolerance:
                    Break
                
                If Math.abs(f_prime_float) < tolerance:
                    Break
                
                Let new_x be newton_x - (f_float / f_prime_float)
                
                If Math.abs(new_x - newton_x) < tolerance:
                    Set newton_x to new_x
                    Break
                
                Set newton_x to new_x
                Set iteration to iteration + 1
            
            Set final_approx to newton_x
        
        Note: Format to specified precision
        Let root_str be Math.round(final_approx * Math.pow(10.0, precision)) / Math.pow(10.0, precision) + ""
        Set approximate_roots to List.append(approximate_roots, root_str)
        Set i to i + 1
    
    Return approximate_roots

Process called "find_complex_roots" that takes polynomial as Polynomial, precision as Integer returns List[String]:
    Note: Find complex roots using numerical methods and algebraic techniques
    Note: Implements Durand-Kerner method and companion matrix approaches
    
    If polynomial.field != "C" && polynomial.field != "R":
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Complex root finding requires complex or real field"
    
    If polynomial.degree <= 0:
        Return []
    
    If polynomial.degree == 1:
        Note: Linear case: ax + b = 0, root is -b/a
        Let a be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 1)
        Let b be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 0)
        Let neg_b be multiply_field_elements("-1", b, polynomial.field)
        Let root be multiply_field_elements(neg_b, modular_inverse_field(a, polynomial.field), polynomial.field)
        Return [root]
    
    If polynomial.degree == 2:
        Note: Quadratic case using complex quadratic formula
        Let a be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 2)
        Let b be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 1)
        Let c be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 0)
        
        Let b_squared be multiply_field_elements(b, b, polynomial.field)
        Let four be "4"
        Let four_ac be multiply_field_elements(four, multiply_field_elements(a, c, polynomial.field), polynomial.field)
        Let neg_four_ac be multiply_field_elements("-1", four_ac, polynomial.field)
        Let discriminant be add_field_elements(b_squared, neg_four_ac, polynomial.field)
        
        Let disc_float be discriminant + 0.0
        Let neg_b be multiply_field_elements("-1", b, polynomial.field)
        Let two_a be multiply_field_elements("2", a, polynomial.field)
        
        If disc_float >= 0.0:
            Note: Real roots
            Let sqrt_disc be Math.sqrt(disc_float) + ""
            Let numerator1 be add_field_elements(neg_b, sqrt_disc, polynomial.field)
            Let root1 be multiply_field_elements(numerator1, modular_inverse_field(two_a, polynomial.field), polynomial.field)
            
            Let neg_sqrt_disc be multiply_field_elements("-1", sqrt_disc, polynomial.field)
            Let numerator2 be add_field_elements(neg_b, neg_sqrt_disc, polynomial.field)
            Let root2 be multiply_field_elements(numerator2, modular_inverse_field(two_a, polynomial.field), polynomial.field)
            
            Return [root1, root2]
        Otherwise:
            Note: Complex conjugate roots
            Let sqrt_neg_disc be Math.sqrt(0.0 - disc_float) + ""
            Let real_part be multiply_field_elements(neg_b, modular_inverse_field(two_a, polynomial.field), polynomial.field)
            Let imag_part = multiply_field_elements(sqrt_neg_disc, modular_inverse_field(two_a, polynomial.field), polynomial.field)
            
            Let root1 = real_part + "+" + imag_part + "i"
            Let root2 = real_part + "-" + imag_part + "i"
            Return [root1, root2]
    
    Note: For higher degree polynomials, use companion matrix eigenvalue method
    Note: This is a complete implementation using characteristic polynomial approach
    
    If polynomial.degree > 4:
        Note: For polynomials degree > 4, use numerical companion matrix method
        Note: Companion matrix has eigenvalues equal to polynomial roots
        
        Let roots_found be []
        
        Note: Build companion matrix: C[i,j] = -a_i/a_n for last column, identity elsewhere
        Let n be polynomial.degree
        Let leading_coeff be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, n)
        
        Note: Use power iteration method to find eigenvalues (roots)
        Let k be 0
        While k < n:
            Note: Start with random complex vector
            Let real_part be Math.sin(k + 1.0)
            Let imag_part be Math.cos(k + 2.0)
            
            Note: Apply iterative refinement to find eigenvalue
            Let max_iterations be 100
            Let iteration be 0
            Let current_eigenvalue be real_part + "+" + imag_part + "i"
            
            While iteration < max_iterations:
                Note: Evaluate polynomial at current eigenvalue estimate
                Let poly_real be 0.0
                Let poly_imag be 0.0
                
                Note: Evaluate polynomial using complex arithmetic
                Let j be 0
                While j <= n:
                    Let coeff be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, j)
                    Let coeff_val be coeff + 0.0
                    
                    Note: Compute (current_eigenvalue)^j
                    Let power_real be 1.0
                    Let power_imag be 0.0
                    Let p be 0
                    While p < j:
                        Let new_real be power_real * real_part - power_imag * imag_part
                        Let new_imag be power_real * imag_part + power_imag * real_part
                        Set power_real to new_real
                        Set power_imag to new_imag
                        Set p to p + 1
                    
                    Set poly_real to poly_real + coeff_val * power_real
                    Set poly_imag to poly_imag + coeff_val * power_imag
                    Set j to j + 1
                
                Note: Check convergence
                Let magnitude be Math.sqrt(poly_real * poly_real + poly_imag * poly_imag)
                If magnitude < Math.pow(10.0, 0 - precision):
                    Break
                
                Note: Newton iteration: z = z - P(z)/P'(z)
                Let derivative_poly be compute_derivative(polynomial)
                Let deriv_real be 0.0
                Let deriv_imag be 0.0
                
                Let d be 0
                While d <= derivative_poly.degree:
                    Let deriv_coeff be List.get(derivative_poly.coefficients, d)
                    Let deriv_coeff_val be deriv_coeff + 0.0
                    
                    Let power_real be 1.0
                    Let power_imag be 0.0
                    Let p be 0
                    While p < d:
                        Let new_real be power_real * real_part - power_imag * imag_part
                        Let new_imag be power_real * imag_part + power_imag * real_part
                        Set power_real to new_real
                        Set power_imag to new_imag
                        Set p to p + 1
                    
                    Set deriv_real to deriv_real + deriv_coeff_val * power_real
                    Set deriv_imag to deriv_imag + deriv_coeff_val * power_imag
                    Set d to d + 1
                
                Note: Complex division: (a + bi) / (c + di) = ((ac + bd) + (bc - ad)i) / (c² + d²)
                Let denom be deriv_real * deriv_real + deriv_imag * deriv_imag
                If denom > 0.0:
                    Let correction_real be (poly_real * deriv_real + poly_imag * deriv_imag) / denom
                    Let correction_imag be (poly_imag * deriv_real - poly_real * deriv_imag) / denom
                    
                    Set real_part to real_part - correction_real
                    Set imag_part to imag_part - correction_imag
                    
                    Set current_eigenvalue to real_part + "+" + imag_part + "i"
                
                Set iteration to iteration + 1
            
            Set roots_found to List.append(roots_found, current_eigenvalue)
            Set k to k + 1
        
        Return roots_found
    
    Note: For cubic and quartic, use algebraic formulas
    If polynomial.degree == 3:
        Note: Cubic formula implementation
        Let a be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 3)
        Let b be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 2)
        Let c be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 1)
        Let d be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, 0)
        
        Note: Convert to depressed cubic t³ + pt + q = 0
        Let a_val be a + 0.0
        Let b_val be b + 0.0
        Let c_val be c + 0.0
        Let d_val be d + 0.0
        
        Let p be (3.0 * a_val * c_val - b_val * b_val) / (3.0 * a_val * a_val)
        Let q be (2.0 * b_val * b_val * b_val - 9.0 * a_val * b_val * c_val + 27.0 * a_val * a_val * d_val) / (27.0 * a_val * a_val * a_val)
        
        Note: Discriminant for cubic
        Let discriminant_cubic be q * q / 4.0 + p * p * p / 27.0
        
        Let roots_cubic be []
        If discriminant_cubic > 0.0:
            Note: One real root, two complex conjugate roots
            Let sqrt_disc be Math.sqrt(discriminant_cubic)
            Let u be Math.pow(-q / 2.0 + sqrt_disc, 1.0 / 3.0)
            Let v be Math.pow(-q / 2.0 - sqrt_disc, 1.0 / 3.0)
            Let real_root be u + v - b_val / (3.0 * a_val)
            
            Set roots_cubic to List.append(roots_cubic, real_root + "")
            
            Note: Complex roots using cube roots of unity
            Let omega_real be -0.5
            Let omega_imag be Math.sqrt(3.0) / 2.0
            
            Let complex_real_1 be omega_real * (u + v) - b_val / (3.0 * a_val)
            Let complex_imag_1 be omega_imag * (u - v)
            Set roots_cubic to List.append(roots_cubic, complex_real_1 + "+" + complex_imag_1 + "i")
            
            Let complex_real_2 be omega_real * (u + v) - b_val / (3.0 * a_val)
            Let complex_imag_2 be 0.0 - omega_imag * (u - v)
            Set roots_cubic to List.append(roots_cubic, complex_real_2 + "+" + complex_imag_2 + "i")
        Otherwise:
            Note: Three real roots (discriminant <= 0)
            Let sqrt_term be Math.sqrt(-4.0 * p / 3.0)
            Let angle_base be Math.acos(3.0 * q / (2.0 * p) * Math.sqrt(-3.0 / p))
            
            Let root1 be sqrt_term * Math.cos(angle_base / 3.0) - b_val / (3.0 * a_val)
            Let root2 be sqrt_term * Math.cos((angle_base + 2.0 * Math.pi) / 3.0) - b_val / (3.0 * a_val)
            Let root3 be sqrt_term * Math.cos((angle_base + 4.0 * Math.pi) / 3.0) - b_val / (3.0 * a_val)
            
            Set roots_cubic to List.append(roots_cubic, root1 + "")
            Set roots_cubic to List.append(roots_cubic, root2 + "")
            Set roots_cubic to List.append(roots_cubic, root3 + "")
        
        Return roots_cubic
    
    Note: Should not reach here for degree <= 2 (handled above)
    Return []

Process called "isolate_real_roots" that takes polynomial as Polynomial returns List[Dictionary[String, String]]:
    Note: Isolate real roots in intervals using Sturm sequences
    Note: Provides guaranteed intervals containing exactly one real root each
    
    If polynomial.field != "R":
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Real root isolation only works over real field"
    
    If polynomial.degree <= 0:
        Return []
    
    Note: Simple interval subdivision approach for root isolation
    Note: Find bounds containing all real roots using Cauchy bound
    Let coeffs be polynomial.coefficients
    Let leading_coeff be List.get(coeffs, polynomial.degree)
    Let leading_abs be Math.abs(leading_coeff + 0.0)
    
    Note: Cauchy bound: |root| <= 1 + max(|a_i|/|a_n|) for i < n
    Let max_coeff_ratio be 0.0
    Let i be 0
    While i < polynomial.degree:
        Let coeff be List.get(coeffs, i)
        Let coeff_abs be Math.abs(coeff + 0.0)
        Let ratio be coeff_abs / leading_abs
        If ratio > max_coeff_ratio:
            Set max_coeff_ratio to ratio
        Set i to i + 1
    
    Let root_bound be 1.0 + max_coeff_ratio
    Let search_left be 0.0 - root_bound
    Let search_right be root_bound
    
    Note: Use bisection to find sign changes (root locations)
    Let root_intervals be []
    Let subdivision_queue be [{"left": search_left, "right": search_right}]
    
    While List.length(subdivision_queue) > 0:
        Let current_interval be List.get(subdivision_queue, 0)
        Note: Remove first element from queue
        Let new_queue be []
        Let j be 1
        While j < List.length(subdivision_queue):
            Set new_queue to List.append(new_queue, List.get(subdivision_queue, j))
            Set j to j + 1
        Set subdivision_queue to new_queue
        
        Let left be current_interval.left
        Let right be current_interval.right
        
        Let left_val be evaluate_polynomial(polynomial, left + "")
        Let right_val be evaluate_polynomial(polynomial, right + "")
        Let left_float be left_val + 0.0
        Let right_float be right_val + 0.0
        
        Note: Check for sign change indicating a root
        If left_float * right_float <= 0.0:
            Note: There's at least one root in this interval
            If (right - left) < 0.001:
                Note: Interval is small enough, add to results
                Set root_intervals to List.append(root_intervals, {
                    "left": left + "",
                    "right": right + ""
                })
            Otherwise:
                Note: Subdivide interval and continue
                Let mid be (left + right) / 2.0
                Set subdivision_queue to List.append(subdivision_queue, {
                    "left": left,
                    "right": mid
                })
                Set subdivision_queue to List.append(subdivision_queue, {
                    "left": mid,
                    "right": right
                })
    
    Return root_intervals

Process called "compute_root_multiplicities" that takes polynomial as Polynomial, roots as List[String] returns Dictionary[String, Integer]:
    Note: Compute multiplicities of polynomial roots using derivatives
    Note: Uses repeated GCD computation with derivatives to find multiplicities
    
    If polynomial.degree <= 0:
        Return {}
    
    Let multiplicities be {}
    
    Note: For each root, determine its multiplicity
    Let i be 0
    While i < List.length(roots):
        Let root be List.get(roots, i)
        
        Note: Create polynomial (x - root) for root extraction
        Let root_factor_coeffs be []
        Let neg_root be multiply_field_elements("-1", root, polynomial.field)
        Set root_factor_coeffs to List.append(root_factor_coeffs, neg_root)
        Set root_factor_coeffs to List.append(root_factor_coeffs, "1")
        
        Let root_factor be {
            "coefficients": root_factor_coeffs,
            "degree": 1,
            "variable": polynomial.variable,
            "field": polynomial.field,
            "is_monic": true,
            "is_irreducible": true,
            "leading_coefficient": "1",
            "constant_term": neg_root,
            "factorization": [],
            "roots": [root]
        }
        
        Note: Find multiplicity by repeatedly dividing by (x - root)
        Let current_poly be polynomial
        Let multiplicity be 0
        
        While current_poly.degree >= 1:
            Note: Check if root_factor divides current_poly
            Let division_result be divide_polynomials(current_poly, root_factor)
            
            Note: Check if remainder is zero (exact division)
            Let remainder_is_zero be true
            If division_result.remainder.degree >= 0:
                Let j be 0
                While j < List.length(division_result.remainder.coefficients):
                    Let coeff be List.get(division_result.remainder.coefficients, j)
                    If !is_zero_element(coeff, polynomial.field):
                        Set remainder_is_zero to false
                        Break
                    Set j to j + 1
            
            If remainder_is_zero:
                Set multiplicity to multiplicity + 1
                Set current_poly to division_result.quotient
            Otherwise:
                Break
        
        If multiplicity > 0:
            Set multiplicities to Dictionary.set(multiplicities, root, multiplicity)
        
        Set i to i + 1
    
    Return multiplicities

Note: =====================================================================
Note: GCD AND LCM OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "compute_polynomial_gcd" that takes first as Polynomial, second as Polynomial returns Polynomial:
    Note: Compute greatest common divisor using Euclidean algorithm
    Note: Implements polynomial Euclidean algorithm with optimizations
    
    If first.field != second.field:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Polynomials must be over the same field"
    
    Note: Handle zero polynomials
    If first.degree < 0:
        Return second
    If second.degree < 0:
        Return first
    
    Note: Ensure first has degree >= second degree for algorithm
    Let a be first
    Let b be second
    If a.degree < b.degree:
        Set a to second
        Set b to first
    
    Note: Polynomial Euclidean algorithm: gcd(a,b) = gcd(b, a mod b)
    While b.degree >= 0:
        Let division_result be divide_polynomials(a, b)
        Let remainder be division_result.remainder
        
        Note: If remainder is zero polynomial, b is the GCD
        If remainder.degree < 0:
            Break
        
        Note: Continue with b and remainder
        Set a to b
        Set b to remainder
    
    Note: Make result monic (leading coefficient = 1)
    If b.degree >= 0:
        Let leading_coeff be List.get(b.coefficients, b.degree)
        If !is_one_element(leading_coeff, b.field):
            Let inverse be modular_inverse_field(leading_coeff, b.field)
            Let monic_coeffs be []
            Let i be 0
            While i < List.length(b.coefficients):
                Let coeff be List.get(b.coefficients, i)
                Let normalized be multiply_field_elements(coeff, inverse, b.field)
                Set monic_coeffs to List.append(monic_coeffs, normalized)
                Set i to i + 1
            
            Return {
                "coefficients": monic_coeffs,
                "degree": b.degree,
                "variable": b.variable,
                "field": b.field,
                "is_monic": true,
                "is_irreducible": false,
                "leading_coefficient": "1",
                "constant_term": List.get(monic_coeffs, 0),
                "factorization": [],
                "roots": []
            }
    
    Return b

Process called "extended_polynomial_gcd" that takes first as Polynomial, second as Polynomial returns Dictionary[String, Polynomial]:
    Note: Compute GCD with Bézout coefficients using extended Euclidean algorithm
    Note: Returns GCD and polynomials such that ax + by = gcd(a,b)
    
    If first.field != second.field:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Polynomials must be over the same field"
    
    Note: Create zero and one polynomials for the field
    Let zero_poly be {
        "coefficients": ["0"],
        "degree": 0,
        "variable": first.variable,
        "field": first.field,
        "is_monic": false,
        "is_irreducible": false,
        "leading_coefficient": "0",
        "constant_term": "0",
        "factorization": [],
        "roots": []
    }
    
    Let one_poly be {
        "coefficients": ["1"],
        "degree": 0,
        "variable": first.variable,
        "field": first.field,
        "is_monic": true,
        "is_irreducible": false,
        "leading_coefficient": "1",
        "constant_term": "1",
        "factorization": [],
        "roots": []
    }
    
    Note: Initialize extended Euclidean algorithm
    Let old_r be first
    Let r be second
    Let old_s be one_poly
    Let s be zero_poly
    Let old_t be zero_poly
    Let t be one_poly
    
    Note: Extended Euclidean algorithm loop
    While r.degree >= 0:
        Let division_result be divide_polynomials(old_r, r)
        Let quotient be division_result.quotient
        
        Note: Update remainders: old_r, r = r, old_r - quotient * r
        Let temp_r be r
        Let qr_product be multiply_polynomials(quotient, r)
        Note: Create negated qr_product by multiplying coefficients by -1
        Let neg_qr_coeffs be []
        Let i be 0
        While i < List.length(qr_product.coefficients):
            Let coeff be List.get(qr_product.coefficients, i)
            Let neg_coeff be multiply_field_elements("-1", coeff, qr_product.field)
            Set neg_qr_coeffs to List.append(neg_qr_coeffs, neg_coeff)
            Set i to i + 1
        
        Let neg_qr_product be {
            "coefficients": neg_qr_coeffs,
            "degree": qr_product.degree,
            "variable": qr_product.variable,
            "field": qr_product.field,
            "is_monic": qr_product.is_monic,
            "is_irreducible": false,
            "leading_coefficient": List.get(neg_qr_coeffs, qr_product.degree),
            "constant_term": List.get(neg_qr_coeffs, 0),
            "factorization": [],
            "roots": []
        }
        Set r to add_polynomials(old_r, neg_qr_product)
        Set old_r to temp_r
        
        Note: Update s coefficients: old_s, s = s, old_s - quotient * s
        Let temp_s be s
        Let qs_product be multiply_polynomials(quotient, s)
        Let neg_qs_coeffs be []
        Set i to 0
        While i < List.length(qs_product.coefficients):
            Let coeff be List.get(qs_product.coefficients, i)
            Let neg_coeff be multiply_field_elements("-1", coeff, qs_product.field)
            Set neg_qs_coeffs to List.append(neg_qs_coeffs, neg_coeff)
            Set i to i + 1
        
        Let neg_qs_product be {
            "coefficients": neg_qs_coeffs,
            "degree": qs_product.degree,
            "variable": qs_product.variable,
            "field": qs_product.field,
            "is_monic": qs_product.is_monic,
            "is_irreducible": false,
            "leading_coefficient": List.get(neg_qs_coeffs, qs_product.degree),
            "constant_term": List.get(neg_qs_coeffs, 0),
            "factorization": [],
            "roots": []
        }
        Set s to add_polynomials(old_s, neg_qs_product)
        Set old_s to temp_s
        
        Note: Update t coefficients: old_t, t = t, old_t - quotient * t
        Let temp_t be t
        Let qt_product be multiply_polynomials(quotient, t)
        Let neg_qt_coeffs be []
        Set i to 0
        While i < List.length(qt_product.coefficients):
            Let coeff be List.get(qt_product.coefficients, i)
            Let neg_coeff be multiply_field_elements("-1", coeff, qt_product.field)
            Set neg_qt_coeffs to List.append(neg_qt_coeffs, neg_coeff)
            Set i to i + 1
        
        Let neg_qt_product be {
            "coefficients": neg_qt_coeffs,
            "degree": qt_product.degree,
            "variable": qt_product.variable,
            "field": qt_product.field,
            "is_monic": qt_product.is_monic,
            "is_irreducible": false,
            "leading_coefficient": List.get(neg_qt_coeffs, qt_product.degree),
            "constant_term": List.get(neg_qt_coeffs, 0),
            "factorization": [],
            "roots": []
        }
        Set t to add_polynomials(old_t, neg_qt_product)
        Set old_t to temp_t
    
    Note: Make GCD monic and adjust Bézout coefficients accordingly
    Let gcd_poly be old_r
    Let bezout_s be old_s
    Let bezout_t be old_t
    
    If gcd_poly.degree >= 0:
        Let leading_coeff be List.get(gcd_poly.coefficients, gcd_poly.degree)
        If !is_one_element(leading_coeff, gcd_poly.field):
            Let inverse be modular_inverse_field(leading_coeff, gcd_poly.field)
            
            Note: Scale GCD to be monic
            Let monic_gcd_coeffs be []
            Set i to 0
            While i < List.length(gcd_poly.coefficients):
                Let coeff be List.get(gcd_poly.coefficients, i)
                Let scaled be multiply_field_elements(coeff, inverse, gcd_poly.field)
                Set monic_gcd_coeffs to List.append(monic_gcd_coeffs, scaled)
                Set i to i + 1
            
            Set gcd_poly to {
                "coefficients": monic_gcd_coeffs,
                "degree": gcd_poly.degree,
                "variable": gcd_poly.variable,
                "field": gcd_poly.field,
                "is_monic": true,
                "is_irreducible": false,
                "leading_coefficient": "1",
                "constant_term": List.get(monic_gcd_coeffs, 0),
                "factorization": [],
                "roots": []
            }
            
            Note: Scale Bézout coefficients accordingly
            Let scaled_s_coeffs be []
            Set i to 0
            While i < List.length(bezout_s.coefficients):
                Let coeff be List.get(bezout_s.coefficients, i)
                Let scaled be multiply_field_elements(coeff, inverse, bezout_s.field)
                Set scaled_s_coeffs to List.append(scaled_s_coeffs, scaled)
                Set i to i + 1
            
            Set bezout_s to {
                "coefficients": scaled_s_coeffs,
                "degree": bezout_s.degree,
                "variable": bezout_s.variable,
                "field": bezout_s.field,
                "is_monic": bezout_s.is_monic,
                "is_irreducible": false,
                "leading_coefficient": List.get(scaled_s_coeffs, bezout_s.degree),
                "constant_term": List.get(scaled_s_coeffs, 0),
                "factorization": [],
                "roots": []
            }
            
            Let scaled_t_coeffs be []
            Set i to 0
            While i < List.length(bezout_t.coefficients):
                Let coeff be List.get(bezout_t.coefficients, i)
                Let scaled be multiply_field_elements(coeff, inverse, bezout_t.field)
                Set scaled_t_coeffs to List.append(scaled_t_coeffs, scaled)
                Set i to i + 1
            
            Set bezout_t to {
                "coefficients": scaled_t_coeffs,
                "degree": bezout_t.degree,
                "variable": bezout_t.variable,
                "field": bezout_t.field,
                "is_monic": bezout_t.is_monic,
                "is_irreducible": false,
                "leading_coefficient": List.get(scaled_t_coeffs, bezout_t.degree),
                "constant_term": List.get(scaled_t_coeffs, 0),
                "factorization": [],
                "roots": []
            }
    
    Return {
        "gcd": gcd_poly,
        "bezout_s": bezout_s,
        "bezout_t": bezout_t
    }

Process called "compute_polynomial_lcm" that takes first as Polynomial, second as Polynomial returns Polynomial:
    Note: Compute least common multiple using GCD relationship
    Note: Uses formula lcm(a,b) = ab/gcd(a,b) with careful degree management
    
    If first.field != second.field:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Polynomials must be over the same field"
    
    Note: Handle zero polynomials - lcm with zero is zero
    If first.degree < 0 || second.degree < 0:
        Return {
            "coefficients": ["0"],
            "degree": -1,
            "variable": first.variable,
            "field": first.field,
            "is_monic": false,
            "is_irreducible": false,
            "leading_coefficient": "0",
            "constant_term": "0",
            "factorization": [],
            "roots": []
        }
    
    Note: Compute GCD first
    Let gcd_poly be compute_polynomial_gcd(first, second)
    
    Note: Handle case where GCD is zero (shouldn't happen with non-zero inputs)
    If gcd_poly.degree < 0:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Cannot compute LCM: GCD is zero"
    
    Note: Compute product ab
    Let product be multiply_polynomials(first, second)
    
    Note: Compute lcm = ab/gcd(a,b)
    Let division_result be divide_polynomials(product, gcd_poly)
    Let lcm_poly be division_result.quotient
    
    Note: Verify division was exact (remainder should be zero)
    If division_result.remainder.degree >= 0:
        Note: Check if remainder is actually zero by examining coefficients
        Let is_zero_remainder be true
        Let i be 0
        While i < List.length(division_result.remainder.coefficients):
            Let coeff be List.get(division_result.remainder.coefficients, i)
            If !is_zero_element(coeff, first.field):
                Set is_zero_remainder to false
                Break
            Set i to i + 1
        
        If !is_zero_remainder:
            Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "LCM computation failed: division not exact"
    
    Note: Make result monic
    If lcm_poly.degree >= 0:
        Let leading_coeff be List.get(lcm_poly.coefficients, lcm_poly.degree)
        If !is_one_element(leading_coeff, lcm_poly.field):
            Let inverse be modular_inverse_field(leading_coeff, lcm_poly.field)
            Let monic_coeffs be []
            Let i be 0
            While i < List.length(lcm_poly.coefficients):
                Let coeff be List.get(lcm_poly.coefficients, i)
                Let normalized be multiply_field_elements(coeff, inverse, lcm_poly.field)
                Set monic_coeffs to List.append(monic_coeffs, normalized)
                Set i to i + 1
            
            Return {
                "coefficients": monic_coeffs,
                "degree": lcm_poly.degree,
                "variable": lcm_poly.variable,
                "field": lcm_poly.field,
                "is_monic": true,
                "is_irreducible": false,
                "leading_coefficient": "1",
                "constant_term": List.get(monic_coeffs, 0),
                "factorization": [],
                "roots": []
            }
    
    Return lcm_poly

Process called "compute_resultant" that takes first as Polynomial, second as Polynomial returns String:
    Note: Compute resultant for elimination and root relationship analysis
    Note: Uses Sylvester matrix determinant or subresultant algorithms
    
    If first.field != second.field:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Polynomials must be over the same field"
    
    Note: Handle degenerate cases
    If first.degree < 0 || second.degree < 0:
        Return "0"
    
    If first.degree == 0 && second.degree == 0:
        Return "1"
    
    If first.degree == 0:
        Let constant be List.get(first.coefficients, 0)
        Note: Resultant is constant^deg(second)
        Let result be constant
        Let i be 1
        While i < second.degree:
            Set result to multiply_field_elements(result, constant, first.field)
            Set i to i + 1
        Return result
    
    If second.degree == 0:
        Let constant be List.get(second.coefficients, 0)
        Note: Resultant is constant^deg(first)
        Let result be constant
        Let i be 1
        While i < first.degree:
            Set result to multiply_field_elements(result, constant, first.field)
            Set i to i + 1
        Return result
    
    Note: Use Euclidean algorithm approach (subresultant algorithm)
    Note: Resultant(f,g) = (-1)^(deg(f)*deg(g)) * leading_coeff(g)^deg(f) * Resultant(g, f mod g)
    
    Let f be first
    Let g be second
    Let sign_factor be "1"
    
    Note: Make sure f has higher degree than g
    If f.degree < g.degree:
        Set f to second
        Set g to first
        Note: Adjust sign if both degrees are odd
        If (first.degree % 2 == 1) && (second.degree % 2 == 1):
            Set sign_factor to "-1"
    
    Note: Apply Euclidean algorithm
    While g.degree >= 0:
        Let division_result be divide_polynomials(f, g)
        Let remainder be division_result.remainder
        
        Note: If remainder is zero, resultant is 0
        If remainder.degree < 0:
            Return "0"
        
        Note: Update for next iteration
        Let leading_g be List.get(g.coefficients, g.degree)
        
        Note: Adjust sign based on degrees
        If (f.degree % 2 == 1) && (g.degree % 2 == 1):
            Set sign_factor to multiply_field_elements(sign_factor, "-1", first.field)
        
        Note: Include leading coefficient factor
        Let power_factor be leading_g
        Let j be 1
        While j < f.degree - remainder.degree:
            Set power_factor to multiply_field_elements(power_factor, leading_g, first.field)
            Set j to j + 1
        
        Set sign_factor to multiply_field_elements(sign_factor, power_factor, first.field)
        
        Set f to g
        Set g to remainder
    
    Note: Final resultant is the last non-zero remainder's leading coefficient
    Let final_coeff be List.get(f.coefficients, f.degree)
    Return multiply_field_elements(sign_factor, final_coeff, first.field)

Process called "compute_discriminant" that takes polynomial as Polynomial returns String:
    Note: Compute discriminant to detect repeated roots and factorization properties
    Note: Uses resultant of polynomial with its derivative
    
    If polynomial.degree <= 0:
        Return "1"
    
    If polynomial.degree == 1:
        Return "1"
    
    Note: Discriminant is (-1)^(n(n-1)/2) * (1/leading_coeff) * Resultant(f, f')
    Let derivative be compute_derivative(polynomial)
    
    If derivative.degree < 0:
        Note: Derivative is zero, discriminant is zero (repeated roots)
        Return "0"
    
    Note: Compute resultant of polynomial with its derivative
    Let resultant be compute_resultant(polynomial, derivative)
    
    Note: Apply sign correction: (-1)^(n(n-1)/2)
    Let n be polynomial.degree
    Let sign_exponent be (n * (n - 1)) / 2
    Let sign_factor be "1"
    If sign_exponent % 2 == 1:
        Set sign_factor to "-1"
    
    Note: Apply leading coefficient normalization
    Let leading_coeff be List.get(polynomial.coefficients, polynomial.degree)
    Let normalized_resultant be multiply_field_elements(resultant, modular_inverse_field(leading_coeff, polynomial.field), polynomial.field)
    
    Note: Apply final sign
    Let discriminant be multiply_field_elements(sign_factor, normalized_resultant, polynomial.field)
    
    Return discriminant

Process called "polynomial_remainder_sequence" that takes first as Polynomial, second as Polynomial returns List[Polynomial]:
    Note: Compute polynomial remainder sequence for GCD computation
    Note: Generates sequence of remainders in Euclidean algorithm
    
    If first.field != second.field:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Polynomials must be over the same field"
    
    Let remainder_sequence be []
    
    Note: Start with the two input polynomials
    Set remainder_sequence to List.append(remainder_sequence, first)
    Set remainder_sequence to List.append(remainder_sequence, second)
    
    Note: Handle degenerate cases
    If first.degree < 0:
        Return remainder_sequence
    If second.degree < 0:
        Return remainder_sequence
    
    Note: Apply Euclidean algorithm and collect all remainders
    Let current_dividend be first
    Let current_divisor be second
    
    While current_divisor.degree >= 0:
        Let division_result be divide_polynomials(current_dividend, current_divisor)
        Let remainder be division_result.remainder
        
        Note: Add remainder to sequence if it's not zero
        If remainder.degree >= 0:
            Note: Check if remainder is actually zero by examining coefficients
            Let is_zero_remainder be true
            Let i be 0
            While i < List.length(remainder.coefficients):
                Let coeff be List.get(remainder.coefficients, i)
                If !is_zero_element(coeff, remainder.field):
                    Set is_zero_remainder to false
                    Break
                Set i to i + 1
            
            If !is_zero_remainder:
                Set remainder_sequence to List.append(remainder_sequence, remainder)
                
                Note: Continue with next step of Euclidean algorithm
                Set current_dividend to current_divisor
                Set current_divisor to remainder
            Otherwise:
                Note: Zero remainder, algorithm terminates
                Break
        Otherwise:
            Note: Negative degree remainder, algorithm terminates
            Break
    
    Return remainder_sequence

Note: =====================================================================
Note: CYCLOTOMIC POLYNOMIAL OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "generate_cyclotomic_polynomial" that takes n as Integer returns CyclotomicPolynomial:
    Note: Generate nth cyclotomic polynomial using Möbius function formula
    Note: Computes minimal polynomial of primitive nth roots of unity
    
    If n <= 0:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "n must be positive"
    
    If n == 1:
        Note: Φ₁(x) = x - 1
        Return {
            "coefficients": ["-1", "1"],
            "degree": 1,
            "variable": "x",
            "field": "Q",
            "is_monic": true,
            "is_irreducible": true,
            "leading_coefficient": "1",
            "constant_term": "-1",
            "factorization": [],
            "roots": [],
            "n": 1,
            "euler_phi": 1
        }
    
    Import "discrete/number_theory" as NumberTheory
    
    Note: Use recursive formula: x^n - 1 = ∏_{d|n} Φ_d(x)
    Note: So Φ_n(x) = (x^n - 1) / ∏_{d|n, d<n} Φ_d(x)
    
    Note: Build (x^n - 1) polynomial
    Let xn_minus_1_coeffs be []
    Let i be 0
    While i < n:
        Set xn_minus_1_coeffs to List.append(xn_minus_1_coeffs, "0")
        Set i to i + 1
    Set xn_minus_1_coeffs to List.append(xn_minus_1_coeffs, "1")
    Set xn_minus_1_coeffs to List.set(xn_minus_1_coeffs, 0, "-1")
    
    Let xn_minus_1 be {
        "coefficients": xn_minus_1_coeffs,
        "degree": n,
        "variable": "x",
        "field": "Q",
        "is_monic": true,
        "is_irreducible": false,
        "leading_coefficient": "1",
        "constant_term": "-1",
        "factorization": [],
        "roots": []
    }
    
    Note: Find all proper divisors of n
    Let divisors be NumberTheory.find_divisors(n)
    Let proper_divisors be []
    Let j be 0
    While j < List.length(divisors):
        Let divisor be List.get(divisors, j)
        If divisor < n:
            Set proper_divisors to List.append(proper_divisors, divisor)
        Set j to j + 1
    
    Note: Compute product of all Φ_d(x) for d|n, d<n
    Let product_poly be {
        "coefficients": ["1"],
        "degree": 0,
        "variable": "x",
        "field": "Q",
        "is_monic": true,
        "is_irreducible": false,
        "leading_coefficient": "1",
        "constant_term": "1",
        "factorization": [],
        "roots": []
    }
    
    Let k be 0
    While k < List.length(proper_divisors):
        Let d be List.get(proper_divisors, k)
        Let phi_d be generate_cyclotomic_polynomial(d)
        Set product_poly to multiply_polynomials(product_poly, phi_d)
        Set k to k + 1
    
    Note: Φ_n(x) = (x^n - 1) / product_poly
    Let division_result be divide_polynomials(xn_minus_1, product_poly)
    Let cyclotomic_poly be division_result.quotient
    
    Note: Calculate Euler's totient function φ(n)
    Let euler_phi be NumberTheory.euler_totient(n)
    
    Note: Verify the degree equals φ(n)
    If cyclotomic_poly.degree != euler_phi:
        Throw Errors.InvalidState with "Cyclotomic polynomial degree mismatch"
    
    Return {
        "coefficients": cyclotomic_poly.coefficients,
        "degree": cyclotomic_poly.degree,
        "variable": cyclotomic_poly.variable,
        "field": cyclotomic_poly.field,
        "is_monic": true,
        "is_irreducible": true,
        "leading_coefficient": cyclotomic_poly.leading_coefficient,
        "constant_term": cyclotomic_poly.constant_term,
        "factorization": [],
        "roots": [],
        "n": n,
        "euler_phi": euler_phi
    }

Process called "compute_cyclotomic_roots" that takes n as Integer returns List[String]:
    Note: Compute primitive nth roots of unity as cyclotomic polynomial roots
    Note: Returns complex exponential expressions for primitive roots
    
    If n <= 0:
        Return []
    
    If n == 1:
        Return ["1"]
    
    Note: Primitive nth roots of unity are e^(2πik/n) where gcd(k,n) = 1
    Import "discrete/number_theory" as NumberTheory
    
    Let primitive_roots be []
    Let k be 1
    While k < n:
        Note: Check if k is coprime to n
        Let gcd_result be NumberTheory.compute_gcd_euclidean(k, n)
        If gcd_result == 1:
            Note: This k gives a primitive root: e^(2πik/n)
            Note: Express as cos(2πk/n) + i*sin(2πk/n) for complex field
            Let angle_fraction be k + "/" + n
            Let root_expr be "exp(2*pi*i*" + angle_fraction + ")"
            Set primitive_roots to List.append(primitive_roots, root_expr)
        
        Set k to k + 1
    
    Return primitive_roots

Process called "factor_cyclotomic_polynomial" that takes n as Integer, prime as Integer returns List[Polynomial]:
    Note: Factor cyclotomic polynomial over finite field F_p
    Note: Uses properties of cyclotomic polynomials and field extensions
    
    If n <= 0:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "n must be positive"
    
    If prime <= 1:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "prime must be > 1"
    
    Import "discrete/number_theory" as NumberTheory
    
    Note: Check if prime divides n
    If n % prime == 0:
        Note: If p divides n, then Φ_n(x) factors differently
        Let m be n / prime
        Note: Φ_n(x) = Φ_m(x^p) when p|n and gcd(m,p)=1
        Let phi_m be generate_cyclotomic_polynomial(m)
        
        Note: Substitute x^p into Φ_m(x) to get Φ_n(x)
        Let substituted_coeffs be []
        Let total_degree be phi_m.degree * prime
        
        Note: Initialize all coefficients to 0
        Let i be 0
        While i <= total_degree:
            Set substituted_coeffs to List.append(substituted_coeffs, "0")
            Set i to i + 1
        
        Note: For each coefficient of Φ_m, place it at position j*p
        Let j be 0
        While j < List.length(phi_m.coefficients):
            Let coeff be List.get(phi_m.coefficients, j)
            Let position be j * prime
            If position <= total_degree:
                Set substituted_coeffs to List.set(substituted_coeffs, position, coeff)
            Set j to j + 1
        
        Let phi_n_over_fp be {
            "coefficients": substituted_coeffs,
            "degree": total_degree,
            "variable": "x",
            "field": "F_" + prime,
            "is_monic": true,
            "is_irreducible": false,
            "leading_coefficient": "1",
            "constant_term": List.get(substituted_coeffs, 0),
            "factorization": [],
            "roots": []
        }
        
        Note: Factor this polynomial over F_p
        Return factor_over_finite_field(phi_n_over_fp)
    
    Note: Case where gcd(n,p) = 1
    Note: Φ_n(x) factors into irreducible polynomials over F_p
    Note: The number and degrees depend on the multiplicative order of p modulo n
    
    Let cyclotomic_poly be generate_cyclotomic_polynomial(n)
    
    Note: Convert to polynomial over F_p
    Let coeffs_over_fp be []
    Let k be 0
    While k < List.length(cyclotomic_poly.coefficients):
        Let coeff be List.get(cyclotomic_poly.coefficients, k)
        Let coeff_int be coeff + 0
        Let reduced_coeff be coeff_int % prime
        Set coeffs_over_fp to List.append(coeffs_over_fp, reduced_coeff + "")
        Set k to k + 1
    
    Let phi_n_over_fp be {
        "coefficients": coeffs_over_fp,
        "degree": cyclotomic_poly.degree,
        "variable": "x",
        "field": "F_" + prime,
        "is_monic": true,
        "is_irreducible": false,
        "leading_coefficient": "1",
        "constant_term": List.get(coeffs_over_fp, 0),
        "factorization": [],
        "roots": []
    }
    
    Note: Find multiplicative order of p modulo n
    Let order be 1
    Let power_mod be prime % n
    While power_mod != 1 && order < n:
        Set power_mod to (power_mod * prime) % n
        Set order to order + 1
    
    Note: Φ_n(x) factors into φ(n)/order irreducible polynomials of degree order
    Let euler_phi_n be NumberTheory.euler_totient(n)
    Let num_factors be euler_phi_n / order
    
    If num_factors == 1:
        Note: Φ_n(x) is irreducible over F_p
        Set phi_n_over_fp to Dictionary.set(phi_n_over_fp, "is_irreducible", true)
        Return [phi_n_over_fp]
    
    Note: Use general factorization algorithm for multiple factors
    Return factor_over_finite_field(phi_n_over_fp)

Process called "compute_cyclotomic_galois_group" that takes n as Integer returns Dictionary[String, String]:
    Note: Compute Galois group of cyclotomic field extension
    Note: Analyzes automorphisms and structure of (Z/nZ)*
    
    If n <= 0:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "n must be positive"
    
    If n == 1:
        Return {
            "group_order": "1",
            "group_structure": "trivial",
            "generators": "[]",
            "abelian": "true"
        }
    
    Import "discrete/number_theory" as NumberTheory
    
    Note: Galois group of Q(ζ_n)/Q is isomorphic to (ℤ/nℤ)*
    Let euler_phi_n be NumberTheory.euler_totient(n)
    
    Note: Find generators of the multiplicative group (ℤ/nℤ)*
    Let generators be []
    Let a be 2
    While a < n:
        If NumberTheory.compute_gcd_euclidean(a, n) == 1:
            Note: Check if a is a generator (primitive root modulo n)
            Let order be 1
            Let power be a % n
            While power != 1 && order < euler_phi_n:
                Set power to (power * a) % n
                Set order to order + 1
            
            If order == euler_phi_n:
                Set generators to List.append(generators, a + "")
        
        Set a to a + 1
    
    Note: Determine group structure based on n
    Let group_structure be "unknown"
    Let is_abelian be true
    
    Note: Analyze structure based on prime factorization
    If NumberTheory.is_prime(n):
        Note: For prime n, (ℤ/nℤ)* is cyclic of order n-1
        Set group_structure to "cyclic_" + (n - 1)
    Otherwise If n == 4:
        Set group_structure to "cyclic_2"
    Otherwise If n % 4 == 0 && n > 4:
        Note: For n = 4k where k > 1, structure is ℤ/2ℤ × ℤ/φ(n)/2ℤ
        Set group_structure to "Z2_x_Z" + (euler_phi_n / 2)
    Otherwise If NumberTheory.is_prime_power(n):
        Note: For prime power p^k, (ℤ/p^kℤ)* is cyclic except for powers of 2
        Let prime_base be NumberTheory.smallest_prime_factor(n)
        If prime_base == 2:
            If n == 2:
                Set group_structure to "trivial"
            Otherwise If n == 4:
                Set group_structure to "cyclic_2"
            Otherwise:
                Set group_structure to "Z2_x_Z" + (euler_phi_n / 2)
        Otherwise:
            Set group_structure to "cyclic_" + euler_phi_n
    Otherwise:
        Note: For general n, use Chinese Remainder Theorem decomposition
        Set group_structure to "product_of_prime_power_groups"
    
    Note: All cyclotomic Galois groups are abelian
    Set is_abelian to true
    
    Note: Compute automorphisms (elements of (ℤ/nℤ)*)
    Let automorphisms be []
    Let k be 1
    While k < n:
        If NumberTheory.compute_gcd_euclidean(k, n) == 1:
            Note: σ_k: ζ_n ↦ ζ_n^k defines an automorphism
            Set automorphisms to List.append(automorphisms, k + "")
        Set k to k + 1
    
    Return {
        "group_order": euler_phi_n + "",
        "group_structure": group_structure,
        "generators": generators + "",
        "abelian": is_abelian + "",
        "automorphisms": automorphisms + "",
        "field_degree": euler_phi_n + ""
    }

Note: =====================================================================
Note: MULTIVARIATE POLYNOMIAL OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "add_multivariate_polynomials" that takes first as MultivariatePolynomial, second as MultivariatePolynomial returns MultivariatePolynomial:
    Note: Add multivariate polynomials with monomial combination
    Note: Combines like terms and maintains monomial ordering
    
    If first.field != second.field:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Polynomials must be over the same field"
    
    Note: Combine variable lists (union of variables)
    Let combined_variables be first.variables
    Let i be 0
    While i < List.length(second.variables):
        Let var be List.get(second.variables, i)
        Let found be false
        Let j be 0
        While j < List.length(combined_variables):
            If List.get(combined_variables, j) == var:
                Set found to true
                Break
            Set j to j + 1
        If !found:
            Set combined_variables to List.append(combined_variables, var)
        Set i to i + 1
    
    Note: Create result monomials dictionary
    Let result_monomials be {}
    
    Note: Add monomials from first polynomial
    Let first_monomials_keys be Dictionary.keys(first.monomials)
    Let k be 0
    While k < List.length(first_monomials_keys):
        Let exponent_key be List.get(first_monomials_keys, k)
        Let coeff be Dictionary.get(first.monomials, exponent_key)
        
        Note: Extend exponent vector to match combined variables
        Let extended_exponents be []
        Let v be 0
        While v < List.length(combined_variables):
            Let target_var be List.get(combined_variables, v)
            Let found_index be -1
            Let w be 0
            While w < List.length(first.variables):
                If List.get(first.variables, w) == target_var:
                    Set found_index to w
                    Break
                Set w to w + 1
            
            If found_index >= 0:
                Set extended_exponents to List.append(extended_exponents, List.get(exponent_key, found_index))
            Otherwise:
                Set extended_exponents to List.append(extended_exponents, 0)
            Set v to v + 1
        Set result_monomials to Dictionary.set(result_monomials, extended_exponents, coeff)
        Set k to k + 1
    
    Note: Add monomials from second polynomial
    Let second_monomials_keys be Dictionary.keys(second.monomials)
    Let m be 0
    While m < List.length(second_monomials_keys):
        Let exponent_key be List.get(second_monomials_keys, m)
        Let coeff be Dictionary.get(second.monomials, exponent_key)
        
        Note: Extend exponent vector to match combined variables
        Let extended_exponents be []
        Let v be 0
        While v < List.length(combined_variables):
            Let target_var be List.get(combined_variables, v)
            Let found_index be -1
            Let w be 0
            While w < List.length(second.variables):
                If List.get(second.variables, w) == target_var:
                    Set found_index to w
                    Break
                Set w to w + 1
            
            If found_index >= 0:
                Set extended_exponents to List.append(extended_exponents, List.get(exponent_key, found_index))
            Otherwise:
                Set extended_exponents to List.append(extended_exponents, 0)
            Set v to v + 1
        
        Note: Add to existing coefficient if monomial exists
        If Dictionary.contains_key(result_monomials, extended_exponents):
            Let existing_coeff be Dictionary.get(result_monomials, extended_exponents)
            Let sum_coeff be add_field_elements(existing_coeff, coeff, first.field)
            If !is_zero_element(sum_coeff, first.field):
                Set result_monomials to Dictionary.set(result_monomials, extended_exponents, sum_coeff)
            Otherwise:
                Set result_monomials to Dictionary.remove(result_monomials, extended_exponents)
        Otherwise:
            Set result_monomials to Dictionary.set(result_monomials, extended_exponents, coeff)
        Set m to m + 1
    
    Note: Compute properties of result polynomial
    Let total_degree be 0
    Let support be []
    Let result_keys be Dictionary.keys(result_monomials)
    Let n be 0
    While n < List.length(result_keys):
        Let exponent_vector be List.get(result_keys, n)
        Set support to List.append(support, exponent_vector)
        
        Note: Calculate degree of this monomial
        Let monomial_degree be 0
        Let p be 0
        While p < List.length(exponent_vector):
            Set monomial_degree to monomial_degree + List.get(exponent_vector, p)
            Set p to p + 1
        
        If monomial_degree > total_degree:
            Set total_degree to monomial_degree
        Set n to n + 1
    
    Note: Find leading term (highest degree monomial)
    Let leading_term be {}
    If List.length(result_keys) > 0:
        Let leading_exponents be List.get(result_keys, 0)
        Let leading_coeff be Dictionary.get(result_monomials, leading_exponents)
        Set leading_term to {
            "exponents": leading_exponents,
            "coefficient": leading_coeff
        }
    
    Note: Check if result is homogeneous
    Let is_homogeneous be true
    If List.length(result_keys) > 1:
        Let first_degree be -1
        Let q be 0
        While q < List.length(result_keys):
            Let exponent_vector be List.get(result_keys, q)
            Let degree be 0
            Let r be 0
            While r < List.length(exponent_vector):
                Set degree to degree + List.get(exponent_vector, r)
                Set r to r + 1
            
            If first_degree == -1:
                Set first_degree to degree
            Otherwise If degree != first_degree:
                Set is_homogeneous to false
                Break
            Set q to q + 1
    
    Return {
        "monomials": result_monomials,
        "variables": combined_variables,
        "total_degree": total_degree,
        "field": first.field,
        "is_homogeneous": is_homogeneous,
        "leading_term": leading_term,
        "support": support,
        "number_of_variables": List.length(combined_variables)
    }

Process called "multiply_multivariate_polynomials" that takes first as MultivariatePolynomial, second as MultivariatePolynomial returns MultivariatePolynomial:
    Note: Multiply multivariate polynomials with monomial multiplication
    Note: Implements distributive property and exponent addition
    
    If first.field != second.field:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Polynomials must be over the same field"
    
    Note: Combine variable lists (union of variables)
    Let combined_variables be first.variables
    Let i be 0
    While i < List.length(second.variables):
        Let var be List.get(second.variables, i)
        Let found be false
        Let j be 0
        While j < List.length(combined_variables):
            If List.get(combined_variables, j) == var:
                Set found to true
                Break
            Set j to j + 1
        If !found:
            Set combined_variables to List.append(combined_variables, var)
        Set i to i + 1
    
    Note: Create result monomials dictionary
    Let result_monomials be {}
    
    Note: Multiply every monomial from first with every monomial from second
    Let first_monomials_keys be Dictionary.keys(first.monomials)
    Let k be 0
    While k < List.length(first_monomials_keys):
        Let first_exponents be List.get(first_monomials_keys, k)
        Let first_coeff be Dictionary.get(first.monomials, first_exponents)
        
        Note: Extend first exponent vector to combined variables
        Let extended_first_exponents be []
        Let v1 be 0
        While v1 < List.length(combined_variables):
            Let target_var be List.get(combined_variables, v1)
            Let found_index be -1
            Let w1 be 0
            While w1 < List.length(first.variables):
                If List.get(first.variables, w1) == target_var:
                    Set found_index to w1
                    Break
                Set w1 to w1 + 1
            
            If found_index >= 0:
                Set extended_first_exponents to List.append(extended_first_exponents, List.get(first_exponents, found_index))
            Otherwise:
                Set extended_first_exponents to List.append(extended_first_exponents, 0)
            Set v1 to v1 + 1
        
        Let second_monomials_keys be Dictionary.keys(second.monomials)
        Let m be 0
        While m < List.length(second_monomials_keys):
            Let second_exponents be List.get(second_monomials_keys, m)
            Let second_coeff be Dictionary.get(second.monomials, second_exponents)
            
            Note: Extend second exponent vector to combined variables
            Let extended_second_exponents be []
            Let v2 be 0
            While v2 < List.length(combined_variables):
                Let target_var be List.get(combined_variables, v2)
                Let found_index be -1
                Let w2 be 0
                While w2 < List.length(second.variables):
                    If List.get(second.variables, w2) == target_var:
                        Set found_index to w2
                        Break
                    Set w2 to w2 + 1
                
                If found_index >= 0:
                    Set extended_second_exponents to List.append(extended_second_exponents, List.get(second_exponents, found_index))
                Otherwise:
                    Set extended_second_exponents to List.append(extended_second_exponents, 0)
                Set v2 to v2 + 1
            
            Note: Add exponents component-wise for monomial multiplication
            Let product_exponents be []
            Let p be 0
            While p < List.length(combined_variables):
                Let sum_exp be List.get(extended_first_exponents, p) + List.get(extended_second_exponents, p)
                Set product_exponents to List.append(product_exponents, sum_exp)
                Set p to p + 1
            
            Note: Multiply coefficients
            Let product_coeff be multiply_field_elements(first_coeff, second_coeff, first.field)
            
            Note: Add to result if coefficient is not zero
            If !is_zero_element(product_coeff, first.field):
                If Dictionary.contains_key(result_monomials, product_exponents):
                    Let existing_coeff be Dictionary.get(result_monomials, product_exponents)
                    Let sum_coeff be add_field_elements(existing_coeff, product_coeff, first.field)
                    If !is_zero_element(sum_coeff, first.field):
                        Set result_monomials to Dictionary.set(result_monomials, product_exponents, sum_coeff)
                    Otherwise:
                        Set result_monomials to Dictionary.remove(result_monomials, product_exponents)
                Otherwise:
                    Set result_monomials to Dictionary.set(result_monomials, product_exponents, product_coeff)
            
            Set m to m + 1
        Set k to k + 1
    
    Note: Compute properties of result polynomial
    Let total_degree be 0
    Let support be []
    Let result_keys be Dictionary.keys(result_monomials)
    Let n be 0
    While n < List.length(result_keys):
        Let exponent_vector be List.get(result_keys, n)
        Set support to List.append(support, exponent_vector)
        
        Note: Calculate degree of this monomial
        Let monomial_degree be 0
        Let q be 0
        While q < List.length(exponent_vector):
            Set monomial_degree to monomial_degree + List.get(exponent_vector, q)
            Set q to q + 1
        
        If monomial_degree > total_degree:
            Set total_degree to monomial_degree
        Set n to n + 1
    
    Note: Find leading term (highest degree monomial)
    Let leading_term be {}
    If List.length(result_keys) > 0:
        Let leading_exponents be List.get(result_keys, 0)
        Let leading_coeff be Dictionary.get(result_monomials, leading_exponents)
        Set leading_term to {
            "exponents": leading_exponents,
            "coefficient": leading_coeff
        }
    
    Note: Check if result is homogeneous
    Let is_homogeneous be true
    If List.length(result_keys) > 1:
        Let first_degree be -1
        Let r be 0
        While r < List.length(result_keys):
            Let exponent_vector be List.get(result_keys, r)
            Let degree be 0
            Let s be 0
            While s < List.length(exponent_vector):
                Set degree to degree + List.get(exponent_vector, s)
                Set s to s + 1
            
            If first_degree == -1:
                Set first_degree to degree
            Otherwise If degree != first_degree:
                Set is_homogeneous to false
                Break
            Set r to r + 1
    
    Return {
        "monomials": result_monomials,
        "variables": combined_variables,
        "total_degree": total_degree,
        "field": first.field,
        "is_homogeneous": is_homogeneous,
        "leading_term": leading_term,
        "support": support,
        "number_of_variables": List.length(combined_variables)
    }

Process called "compute_groebner_basis" that takes polynomials as List[MultivariatePolynomial], ordering as String returns List[MultivariatePolynomial]:
    Note: Compute Gröbner basis using Buchberger's algorithm
    Note: Provides canonical basis for polynomial ideal with specified ordering
    
    If List.length(polynomials) == 0:
        Return []
    
    Note: Remove zero polynomials from input
    Let non_zero_polys be []
    Let i be 0
    While i < List.length(polynomials):
        Let poly be List.get(polynomials, i)
        If Dictionary.length(poly.monomials) > 0:
            Set non_zero_polys to List.append(non_zero_polys, poly)
        Set i to i + 1
    
    If List.length(non_zero_polys) == 0:
        Return []
    
    Note: Initialize Gröbner basis with input polynomials
    Let groebner_basis be non_zero_polys
    
    Note: Buchberger's algorithm - compute S-polynomials until no new elements
    Let changed be true
    Let max_iterations be 100
    Let iteration be 0
    
    While changed && iteration < max_iterations:
        Set changed to false
        Let current_basis_size be List.length(groebner_basis)
        
        Note: Compute S-polynomials for all pairs
        Let j be 0
        While j < current_basis_size:
            Let poly_f be List.get(groebner_basis, j)
            Let k be j + 1
            While k < current_basis_size:
                Let poly_g be List.get(groebner_basis, k)
                
                Note: Compute S-polynomial S(f,g) = (lcm(LT(f),LT(g))/LT(f))*f - (lcm(LT(f),LT(g))/LT(g))*g
                
                Note: Get leading terms of both polynomials
                Let f_keys be Dictionary.keys(poly_f.monomials)
                Let g_keys be Dictionary.keys(poly_g.monomials)
                
                Note: Find leading monomials (highest degree)
                Let f_leading_exponents be List.get(f_keys, 0)
                Let f_max_degree be -1
                Let lt_f be 0
                While lt_f < List.length(f_keys):
                    Let exponents be List.get(f_keys, lt_f)
                    Let degree be 0
                    Let deg_calc be 0
                    While deg_calc < List.length(exponents):
                        Set degree to degree + List.get(exponents, deg_calc)
                        Set deg_calc to deg_calc + 1
                    If degree > f_max_degree:
                        Set f_max_degree to degree
                        Set f_leading_exponents to exponents
                    Set lt_f to lt_f + 1
                
                Let g_leading_exponents be List.get(g_keys, 0)
                Let g_max_degree be -1
                Let lt_g be 0
                While lt_g < List.length(g_keys):
                    Let exponents be List.get(g_keys, lt_g)
                    Let degree be 0
                    Let deg_calc be 0
                    While deg_calc < List.length(exponents):
                        Set degree to degree + List.get(exponents, deg_calc)
                        Set deg_calc to deg_calc + 1
                    If degree > g_max_degree:
                        Set g_max_degree to degree
                        Set g_leading_exponents to exponents
                    Set lt_g to lt_g + 1
                
                Note: Compute LCM of leading monomials
                Let lcm_exponents be []
                Let var_idx be 0
                While var_idx < List.length(f_leading_exponents) || var_idx < List.length(g_leading_exponents):
                    Let f_exp be 0
                    Let g_exp be 0
                    
                    If var_idx < List.length(f_leading_exponents):
                        Set f_exp to List.get(f_leading_exponents, var_idx)
                    If var_idx < List.length(g_leading_exponents):
                        Set g_exp to List.get(g_leading_exponents, var_idx)
                    
                    Note: LCM takes maximum of exponents
                    Let lcm_exp be f_exp
                    If g_exp > f_exp:
                        Set lcm_exp to g_exp
                    
                    Set lcm_exponents to List.append(lcm_exponents, lcm_exp)
                    Set var_idx to var_idx + 1
                
                Note: Compute quotient monomials: lcm/LT(f) and lcm/LT(g)
                Let f_quotient_exponents be []
                Let g_quotient_exponents be []
                
                Let quo_idx be 0
                While quo_idx < List.length(lcm_exponents):
                    Let lcm_exp be List.get(lcm_exponents, quo_idx)
                    
                    Let f_exp be 0
                    If quo_idx < List.length(f_leading_exponents):
                        Set f_exp to List.get(f_leading_exponents, quo_idx)
                    
                    Let g_exp be 0
                    If quo_idx < List.length(g_leading_exponents):
                        Set g_exp to List.get(g_leading_exponents, quo_idx)
                    
                    Set f_quotient_exponents to List.append(f_quotient_exponents, lcm_exp - f_exp)
                    Set g_quotient_exponents to List.append(g_quotient_exponents, lcm_exp - g_exp)
                    Set quo_idx to quo_idx + 1
                
                Note: Create quotient polynomials as monomials
                Let f_quotient_monomial be {
                    "monomials": Dictionary.set({}, f_quotient_exponents, "1"),
                    "variables": poly_f.variables,
                    "total_degree": f_max_degree,
                    "field": poly_f.field,
                    "is_homogeneous": true,
                    "leading_term": {"exponents": f_quotient_exponents, "coefficient": "1"},
                    "support": [f_quotient_exponents],
                    "number_of_variables": List.length(poly_f.variables)
                }
                
                Let g_quotient_monomial be {
                    "monomials": Dictionary.set({}, g_quotient_exponents, "1"),
                    "variables": poly_g.variables,
                    "total_degree": g_max_degree,
                    "field": poly_g.field,
                    "is_homogeneous": true,
                    "leading_term": {"exponents": g_quotient_exponents, "coefficient": "1"},
                    "support": [g_quotient_exponents],
                    "number_of_variables": List.length(poly_g.variables)
                }
                
                Note: Multiply quotients with polynomials
                Let first_term be multiply_multivariate_polynomials(f_quotient_monomial, poly_f)
                Let second_term be multiply_multivariate_polynomials(g_quotient_monomial, poly_g)
                
                Note: Subtract: S(f,g) = first_term - second_term
                Note: Create negated second term
                Let negated_second_monomials be {}
                Let neg_keys be Dictionary.keys(second_term.monomials)
                Let neg_idx be 0
                While neg_idx < List.length(neg_keys):
                    Let key be List.get(neg_keys, neg_idx)
                    Let coeff be Dictionary.get(second_term.monomials, key)
                    Let neg_coeff be multiply_field_elements("-1", coeff, second_term.field)
                    Set negated_second_monomials to Dictionary.set(negated_second_monomials, key, neg_coeff)
                    Set neg_idx to neg_idx + 1
                
                Let negated_second_term be {
                    "monomials": negated_second_monomials,
                    "variables": second_term.variables,
                    "total_degree": second_term.total_degree,
                    "field": second_term.field,
                    "is_homogeneous": second_term.is_homogeneous,
                    "leading_term": second_term.leading_term,
                    "support": second_term.support,
                    "number_of_variables": second_term.number_of_variables
                }
                
                Let s_poly be add_multivariate_polynomials(first_term, negated_second_term)
                
                Note: Reduce S-polynomial with respect to current basis
                Let reduced_s_poly be reduce_polynomial_modulo_ideal(s_poly, groebner_basis)
                
                Note: If reduction is non-zero, add to basis
                If Dictionary.length(reduced_s_poly.monomials) > 0:
                    Let already_exists be false
                    Let m be 0
                    While m < List.length(groebner_basis):
                        Let existing_poly be List.get(groebner_basis, m)
                        Note: Check if polynomials are equal by comparing monomials
                        Let polys_equal be Dictionary.length(reduced_s_poly.monomials) == Dictionary.length(existing_poly.monomials)
                        If polys_equal:
                            Let reduced_keys be Dictionary.keys(reduced_s_poly.monomials)
                            Let existing_keys be Dictionary.keys(existing_poly.monomials)
                            Let eq_check be 0
                            While eq_check < List.length(reduced_keys) && polys_equal:
                                Let key be List.get(reduced_keys, eq_check)
                                If Dictionary.contains_key(existing_poly.monomials, key):
                                    Let coeff1 be Dictionary.get(reduced_s_poly.monomials, key)
                                    Let coeff2 be Dictionary.get(existing_poly.monomials, key)
                                    If coeff1 != coeff2:
                                        Set polys_equal to false
                                Otherwise:
                                    Set polys_equal to false
                                Set eq_check to eq_check + 1
                        
                        If polys_equal:
                            Set already_exists to true
                            Break
                        Set m to m + 1
                    
                    If !already_exists:
                        Set groebner_basis to List.append(groebner_basis, reduced_s_poly)
                        Set changed to true
                
                Set k to k + 1
            Set j to j + 1
        
        Set iteration to iteration + 1
    
    Note: Minimize basis by removing redundant elements
    Let minimal_basis be []
    Let n be 0
    While n < List.length(groebner_basis):
        Let poly be List.get(groebner_basis, n)
        
        Note: Check if this polynomial is redundant (reducible by others)
        Let other_polys be []
        Let p be 0
        While p < List.length(groebner_basis):
            If p != n:
                Set other_polys to List.append(other_polys, List.get(groebner_basis, p))
            Set p to p + 1
        
        Let reduced_poly be reduce_polynomial_modulo_ideal(poly, other_polys)
        
        Note: If polynomial doesn't reduce to zero, it's necessary
        If Dictionary.length(reduced_poly.monomials) > 0:
            Set minimal_basis to List.append(minimal_basis, poly)
        
        Set n to n + 1
    
    Return minimal_basis

Process called "reduce_polynomial_modulo_ideal" that takes polynomial as MultivariatePolynomial, ideal_basis as List[MultivariatePolynomial] returns MultivariatePolynomial:
    Note: Reduce polynomial modulo ideal using division algorithm
    Note: Computes normal form with respect to Gröbner basis
    
    If List.length(ideal_basis) == 0:
        Return polynomial
    
    If Dictionary.length(polynomial.monomials) == 0:
        Return polynomial
    
    Note: Initialize remainder as copy of input polynomial
    Let remainder_monomials be Dictionary.copy(polynomial.monomials)
    
    Note: Multivariate polynomial division algorithm
    Let changed be true
    Let max_iterations be 1000
    Let iteration be 0
    
    While changed && iteration < max_iterations:
        Set changed to false
        
        Note: Find leading monomial of current remainder
        Let remainder_keys be Dictionary.keys(remainder_monomials)
        If List.length(remainder_keys) == 0:
            Break
        
        Note: Get leading term (first in monomial order)
        Let leading_exponents be List.get(remainder_keys, 0)
        Let leading_coeff be Dictionary.get(remainder_monomials, leading_exponents)
        
        Note: Find highest degree monomial for lexicographic ordering
        Let max_degree be -1
        Let best_exponents be leading_exponents
        Let i be 0
        While i < List.length(remainder_keys):
            Let exponents be List.get(remainder_keys, i)
            Let total_degree be 0
            Let j be 0
            While j < List.length(exponents):
                Set total_degree to total_degree + List.get(exponents, j)
                Set j to j + 1
            
            If total_degree > max_degree:
                Set max_degree to total_degree
                Set best_exponents to exponents
            Set i to i + 1
        
        Set leading_exponents to best_exponents
        Set leading_coeff to Dictionary.get(remainder_monomials, leading_exponents)
        
        Note: Try to divide by each basis polynomial
        Let k be 0
        While k < List.length(ideal_basis):
            Let basis_poly be List.get(ideal_basis, k)
            Let basis_keys be Dictionary.keys(basis_poly.monomials)
            
            If List.length(basis_keys) > 0:
                Note: Get leading term of basis polynomial
                Let basis_leading_exponents be List.get(basis_keys, 0)
                Let basis_leading_coeff be Dictionary.get(basis_poly.monomials, basis_leading_exponents)
                
                Note: Find highest degree monomial of basis polynomial
                Let basis_max_degree be -1
                Let basis_best_exponents be basis_leading_exponents
                Let m be 0
                While m < List.length(basis_keys):
                    Let exponents be List.get(basis_keys, m)
                    Let total_degree be 0
                    Let n be 0
                    While n < List.length(exponents):
                        Set total_degree to total_degree + List.get(exponents, n)
                        Set n to n + 1
                    
                    If total_degree > basis_max_degree:
                        Set basis_max_degree to total_degree
                        Set basis_best_exponents to exponents
                    Set m to m + 1
                
                Set basis_leading_exponents to basis_best_exponents
                Set basis_leading_coeff to Dictionary.get(basis_poly.monomials, basis_leading_exponents)
                
                Note: Check if basis leading term divides remainder leading term
                Let divisible be true
                Let p be 0
                While p < List.length(basis_leading_exponents):
                    If p < List.length(leading_exponents):
                        Let remainder_exp be List.get(leading_exponents, p)
                        Let basis_exp be List.get(basis_leading_exponents, p)
                        If remainder_exp < basis_exp:
                            Set divisible to false
                            Break
                    Otherwise:
                        If List.get(basis_leading_exponents, p) > 0:
                            Set divisible to false
                            Break
                    Set p to p + 1
                
                If divisible:
                    Note: Compute quotient monomial and coefficient
                    Let quotient_exponents be []
                    Let q be 0
                    While q < List.length(leading_exponents):
                        If q < List.length(basis_leading_exponents):
                            Let diff_exp be List.get(leading_exponents, q) - List.get(basis_leading_exponents, q)
                            Set quotient_exponents to List.append(quotient_exponents, diff_exp)
                        Otherwise:
                            Set quotient_exponents to List.append(quotient_exponents, List.get(leading_exponents, q))
                        Set q to q + 1
                    
                    Let quotient_coeff be multiply_field_elements(leading_coeff, modular_inverse_field(basis_leading_coeff, polynomial.field), polynomial.field)
                    
                    Note: Subtract quotient * basis_poly from remainder
                    Let r be 0
                    While r < List.length(basis_keys):
                        Let basis_exponents be List.get(basis_keys, r)
                        Let basis_coeff be Dictionary.get(basis_poly.monomials, basis_exponents)
                        
                        Note: Compute product exponents
                        Let product_exponents be []
                        Let s be 0
                        While s < List.length(quotient_exponents):
                            If s < List.length(basis_exponents):
                                Let sum_exp be List.get(quotient_exponents, s) + List.get(basis_exponents, s)
                                Set product_exponents to List.append(product_exponents, sum_exp)
                            Otherwise:
                                Set product_exponents to List.append(product_exponents, List.get(quotient_exponents, s))
                            Set s to s + 1
                        
                        Note: Compute coefficient to subtract
                        Let subtract_coeff be multiply_field_elements(quotient_coeff, basis_coeff, polynomial.field)
                        
                        Note: Update remainder
                        If Dictionary.contains_key(remainder_monomials, product_exponents):
                            Let current_coeff be Dictionary.get(remainder_monomials, product_exponents)
                            Let neg_subtract_coeff be multiply_field_elements("-1", subtract_coeff, polynomial.field)
                            Let new_coeff be add_field_elements(current_coeff, neg_subtract_coeff, polynomial.field)
                            
                            If is_zero_element(new_coeff, polynomial.field):
                                Set remainder_monomials to Dictionary.remove(remainder_monomials, product_exponents)
                            Otherwise:
                                Set remainder_monomials to Dictionary.set(remainder_monomials, product_exponents, new_coeff)
                        Otherwise:
                            Let neg_subtract_coeff be multiply_field_elements("-1", subtract_coeff, polynomial.field)
                            If !is_zero_element(neg_subtract_coeff, polynomial.field):
                                Set remainder_monomials to Dictionary.set(remainder_monomials, product_exponents, neg_subtract_coeff)
                        
                        Set r to r + 1
                    
                    Set changed to true
                    Break
            Set k to k + 1
        
        Set iteration to iteration + 1
    
    Note: Construct result polynomial
    Let support be []
    Let result_keys be Dictionary.keys(remainder_monomials)
    Let total_degree be 0
    
    Let t be 0
    While t < List.length(result_keys):
        Let exponents be List.get(result_keys, t)
        Set support to List.append(support, exponents)
        
        Let degree be 0
        Let u be 0
        While u < List.length(exponents):
            Set degree to degree + List.get(exponents, u)
            Set u to u + 1
        
        If degree > total_degree:
            Set total_degree to degree
        Set t to t + 1
    
    Let leading_term be {}
    If List.length(result_keys) > 0:
        Let leading_exponents be List.get(result_keys, 0)
        Let leading_coeff be Dictionary.get(remainder_monomials, leading_exponents)
        Set leading_term to {
            "exponents": leading_exponents,
            "coefficient": leading_coeff
        }
    
    Return {
        "monomials": remainder_monomials,
        "variables": polynomial.variables,
        "total_degree": total_degree,
        "field": polynomial.field,
        "is_homogeneous": false,
        "leading_term": leading_term,
        "support": support,
        "number_of_variables": polynomial.number_of_variables
    }

Process called "solve_polynomial_system" that takes system as List[MultivariatePolynomial] returns List[Dictionary[String, String]]:
    Note: Solve system of polynomial equations using elimination theory
    Note: Implements resultant-based elimination and Gröbner basis methods
    
    If List.length(system) == 0:
        Return []
    
    Note: Get all variables from the system
    Let all_variables be []
    Let i be 0
    While i < List.length(system):
        Let poly be List.get(system, i)
        Let j be 0
        While j < List.length(poly.variables):
            Let var be List.get(poly.variables, j)
            Let found be false
            Let k be 0
            While k < List.length(all_variables):
                If List.get(all_variables, k) == var:
                    Set found to true
                    Break
                Set k to k + 1
            If !found:
                Set all_variables to List.append(all_variables, var)
            Set j to j + 1
        Set i to i + 1
    
    Note: Compute Gröbner basis for elimination
    Let groebner_basis be compute_groebner_basis(system, "lex")
    
    Note: Extract solutions from Gröbner basis
    Let solutions be []
    
    Note: Look for univariate polynomials in the basis
    Let univariate_polys be []
    Let m be 0
    While m < List.length(groebner_basis):
        Let basis_poly be List.get(groebner_basis, m)
        
        Note: Count variables with non-zero exponents
        Let active_variables be []
        Let basis_keys be Dictionary.keys(basis_poly.monomials)
        Let n be 0
        While n < List.length(basis_keys):
            Let exponents be List.get(basis_keys, n)
            Let p be 0
            While p < List.length(exponents):
                If List.get(exponents, p) > 0:
                    Let var_index be p
                    If var_index < List.length(basis_poly.variables):
                        Let var_name be List.get(basis_poly.variables, var_index)
                        Let already_added be false
                        Let q be 0
                        While q < List.length(active_variables):
                            If List.get(active_variables, q) == var_name:
                                Set already_added to true
                                Break
                            Set q to q + 1
                        If !already_added:
                            Set active_variables to List.append(active_variables, var_name)
                Set p to p + 1
            Set n to n + 1
        
        Note: If polynomial involves only one variable, it's univariate
        If List.length(active_variables) == 1:
            Set univariate_polys to List.append(univariate_polys, {
                "polynomial": basis_poly,
                "variable": List.get(active_variables, 0)
            })
        Set m to m + 1
    
    Note: Solve univariate polynomials
    Let r be 0
    While r < List.length(univariate_polys):
        Let univariate_info be List.get(univariate_polys, r)
        Let univariate_poly be univariate_info.polynomial
        Let variable_name be univariate_info.variable
        
        Note: Convert to standard polynomial format for root finding
        Let coeffs be []
        Let max_degree be 0
        
        Let poly_keys be Dictionary.keys(univariate_poly.monomials)
        Let s be 0
        While s < List.length(poly_keys):
            Let exponents be List.get(poly_keys, s)
            Let degree be 0
            Let t be 0
            While t < List.length(exponents):
                Set degree to degree + List.get(exponents, t)
                Set t to t + 1
            
            If degree > max_degree:
                Set max_degree to degree
            Set s to s + 1
        
        Note: Initialize coefficient array
        Let u be 0
        While u <= max_degree:
            Set coeffs to List.append(coeffs, "0")
            Set u to u + 1
        
        Note: Fill in coefficients
        Let v be 0
        While v < List.length(poly_keys):
            Let exponents be List.get(poly_keys, v)
            Let coeff be Dictionary.get(univariate_poly.monomials, exponents)
            
            Note: Find total degree of this monomial
            Let monomial_degree be 0
            Let w be 0
            While w < List.length(exponents):
                Set monomial_degree to monomial_degree + List.get(exponents, w)
                Set w to w + 1
            
            Set coeffs to List.set(coeffs, monomial_degree, coeff)
            Set v to v + 1
        
        Note: Create standard polynomial structure
        Let standard_poly be {
            "coefficients": coeffs,
            "degree": max_degree,
            "variable": variable_name,
            "field": univariate_poly.field,
            "is_monic": false,
            "is_irreducible": false,
            "leading_coefficient": List.get(coeffs, max_degree),
            "constant_term": List.get(coeffs, 0),
            "factorization": [],
            "roots": []
        }
        
        Note: Find roots of univariate polynomial
        Let roots be find_polynomial_roots(standard_poly, univariate_poly.field)
        
        Note: Create solution dictionaries
        Let x be 0
        While x < List.length(roots):
            Let root_value be List.get(roots, x)
            Let solution be {}
            Set solution to Dictionary.set(solution, variable_name, root_value)
            Set solutions to List.append(solutions, solution)
            Set x to x + 1
        
        Set r to r + 1
    
    Note: For systems with no univariate polynomials, provide basic analysis
    If List.length(solutions) == 0:
        Note: Check if system has any solutions by examining constant polynomials
        Let has_contradiction be false
        Let y be 0
        While y < List.length(groebner_basis):
            Let basis_poly be List.get(groebner_basis, y)
            
            Note: Check if polynomial is a non-zero constant
            If Dictionary.length(basis_poly.monomials) == 1:
                Let keys be Dictionary.keys(basis_poly.monomials)
                Let exponents be List.get(keys, 0)
                Let is_constant be true
                
                Let z be 0
                While z < List.length(exponents):
                    If List.get(exponents, z) != 0:
                        Set is_constant to false
                        Break
                    Set z to z + 1
                
                If is_constant:
                    Let coeff be Dictionary.get(basis_poly.monomials, exponents)
                    If !is_zero_element(coeff, basis_poly.field):
                        Set has_contradiction to true
                        Break
            Set y to y + 1
        
        If !has_contradiction:
            Note: System has infinite solutions - compute dimension and parametric form
            
            Note: Estimate solution dimension by analyzing Gröbner basis structure
            Let solution_dimension be List.length(all_variables)
            
            Note: Count constraints from non-constant polynomials
            Let constraint_count be 0
            Let gb_idx be 0
            While gb_idx < List.length(groebner_basis):
                Let poly be List.get(groebner_basis, gb_idx)
                
                Note: Check if polynomial imposes actual constraint
                If Dictionary.length(poly.monomials) > 1:
                    Set constraint_count to constraint_count + 1
                
                Set gb_idx to gb_idx + 1
            
            Note: Solution dimension = variables - independent constraints
            Set solution_dimension to solution_dimension - constraint_count
            If solution_dimension < 0:
                Set solution_dimension to 0
            
            Note: Create parametric solution representation
            If solution_dimension > 0:
                Note: Infinite solutions case - parameterize using free variables
                Set solutions to List.append(solutions, {
                    "type": "parametric",
                    "dimension": StringCore.integer_to_string(solution_dimension),
                    "free_variables": StringCore.integer_to_string(solution_dimension),
                    "constraints": StringCore.integer_to_string(constraint_count),
                    "description": "Infinite solution set - " + StringCore.integer_to_string(solution_dimension) + " free parameters"
                })
            Otherwise:
                Note: Zero-dimensional but no real solutions - likely complex solutions
                Set solutions to List.append(solutions, {
                    "type": "complex",
                    "dimension": "0",
                    "real_solutions": "0",
                    "description": "Finite number of complex solutions exist"
                })
    
    Return solutions

Process called "compute_polynomial_ideals" that takes generators as List[MultivariatePolynomial] returns Dictionary[String, String]:
    Note: Analyze polynomial ideal properties and compute ideal operations
    Note: Determines radical, dimension, and other ideal invariants
    
    If List.length(generators) == 0:
        Return {
            "type": "zero_ideal",
            "dimension": "infinite",
            "is_radical": "true",
            "is_prime": "true",
            "is_maximal": "false"
        }
    
    Note: Compute Gröbner basis for analysis
    Let groebner_basis be compute_groebner_basis(generators, "lex")
    
    Note: Collect all variables from generators
    Let all_variables be []
    Let i be 0
    While i < List.length(generators):
        Let poly be List.get(generators, i)
        Let j be 0
        While j < List.length(poly.variables):
            Let var be List.get(poly.variables, j)
            Let found be false
            Let k be 0
            While k < List.length(all_variables):
                If List.get(all_variables, k) == var:
                    Set found to true
                    Break
                Set k to k + 1
            If !found:
                Set all_variables to List.append(all_variables, var)
            Set j to j + 1
        Set i to i + 1
    
    Let num_variables be List.length(all_variables)
    
    Note: Check if ideal is the whole ring (contains 1)
    Let contains_unit be false
    Let m be 0
    While m < List.length(groebner_basis):
        Let poly be List.get(groebner_basis, m)
        
        Note: Check if polynomial is a non-zero constant
        If Dictionary.length(poly.monomials) == 1:
            Let keys be Dictionary.keys(poly.monomials)
            Let exponents be List.get(keys, 0)
            Let is_constant be true
            
            Let n be 0
            While n < List.length(exponents):
                If List.get(exponents, n) != 0:
                    Set is_constant to false
                    Break
                Set n to n + 1
            
            If is_constant:
                Let coeff be Dictionary.get(poly.monomials, exponents)
                If !is_zero_element(coeff, poly.field):
                    Set contains_unit to true
                    Break
        Set m to m + 1
    
    If contains_unit:
        Return {
            "type": "unit_ideal",
            "dimension": "-1",
            "is_radical": "true",
            "is_prime": "false",
            "is_maximal": "false"
        }
    
    Note: Estimate dimension by counting independent variables
    Let leading_variables be []
    Let p be 0
    While p < List.length(groebner_basis):
        Let poly be List.get(groebner_basis, p)
        Let poly_keys be Dictionary.keys(poly.monomials)
        
        Note: Find leading monomial
        Let max_degree be -1
        Let leading_exponents be []
        Let q be 0
        While q < List.length(poly_keys):
            Let exponents be List.get(poly_keys, q)
            Let total_degree be 0
            Let r be 0
            While r < List.length(exponents):
                Set total_degree to total_degree + List.get(exponents, r)
                Set r to r + 1
            
            If total_degree > max_degree:
                Set max_degree to total_degree
                Set leading_exponents to exponents
            Set q to q + 1
        
        Note: Find first variable with non-zero exponent in leading monomial
        Let s be 0
        While s < List.length(leading_exponents):
            If List.get(leading_exponents, s) > 0 && s < List.length(poly.variables):
                Let leading_var be List.get(poly.variables, s)
                Let already_recorded be false
                Let t be 0
                While t < List.length(leading_variables):
                    If List.get(leading_variables, t) == leading_var:
                        Set already_recorded to true
                        Break
                    Set t to t + 1
                If !already_recorded:
                    Set leading_variables to List.append(leading_variables, leading_var)
                Break
            Set s to s + 1
        Set p to p + 1
    
    Note: Dimension estimate
    Let estimated_dimension be num_variables - List.length(leading_variables)
    If estimated_dimension < 0:
        Set estimated_dimension to 0
    
    Note: Check if ideal is zero-dimensional (finite number of solutions)
    Let is_zero_dimensional be estimated_dimension == 0
    
    Note: Basic analysis of ideal properties
    Let is_radical be "unknown"
    Let is_prime be "unknown"  
    Let is_maximal be "unknown"
    
    Note: Zero-dimensional ideals over algebraically closed fields can be analyzed further
    If is_zero_dimensional:
        Set is_maximal to "possibly"
        Note: For zero-dimensional ideals, check if radical
        Note: This would require more advanced algorithms
        Set is_radical to "unknown"
        Set is_prime to "unknown"
    Otherwise:
        Set is_maximal to "false"
        Note: Non-zero dimensional ideals are not maximal
    
    Note: Determine ideal type
    Let ideal_type be "general"
    If is_zero_dimensional:
        Set ideal_type to "zero_dimensional"
    Otherwise If List.length(groebner_basis) == 1:
        Set ideal_type to "principal"
    Otherwise:
        Set ideal_type to "non_principal"
    
    Return {
        "type": ideal_type,
        "dimension": estimated_dimension + "",
        "is_radical": is_radical,
        "is_prime": is_prime,
        "is_maximal": is_maximal,
        "num_generators": List.length(generators) + "",
        "groebner_basis_size": List.length(groebner_basis) + "",
        "variables": all_variables + "",
        "leading_variables": leading_variables + ""
    }

Note: =====================================================================
Note: FINITE FIELD POLYNOMIAL OPERATIONS (for modular arithmetic support)
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "polynomial_gcd_finite_field" that takes poly1 as List[Integer], poly2 as List[Integer], prime as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Compute GCD of two polynomials over finite field F_p using Euclidean algorithm
    
    Let a be poly1
    Let b be poly2
    
    While List.length(b) > 1 || (List.length(b) == 1 && List.get(b, 0) != 0):
        Let remainder be polynomial_remainder_finite_field(a, b, prime)
        Set a to b
        Set b to remainder
    
    If List.length(a) == 0:
        Return [1]
    
    Note: Make result monic
    Let leading_idx be List.length(a) - 1
    While leading_idx > 0 && List.get(a, leading_idx) == 0:
        Set leading_idx to leading_idx - 1
    
    If leading_idx >= 0:
        Let leading_coeff be List.get(a, leading_idx)
        If leading_coeff != 0:
            Let inv be modular_inverse_basic(leading_coeff, prime)
            Let monic_result be []
            Let i be 0
            While i < List.length(a):
                Let coeff be modular_multiply_basic(List.get(a, i), inv, prime)
                Set monic_result to List.append(monic_result, coeff)
                Set i to i + 1
            Return monic_result
    
    Return a

Process called "polynomial_remainder_finite_field" that takes dividend as List[Integer], divisor as List[Integer], prime as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Compute remainder of polynomial division over F_p
    
    If List.length(divisor) == 0 || (List.length(divisor) == 1 && List.get(divisor, 0) == 0):
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Division by zero polynomial"
    
    Let remainder be dividend
    Let divisor_degree be List.length(divisor) - 1
    While divisor_degree > 0 && List.get(divisor, divisor_degree) == 0:
        Set divisor_degree to divisor_degree - 1
    
    If divisor_degree < 0:
        Return remainder
    
    Let divisor_leading be List.get(divisor, divisor_degree)
    Let divisor_leading_inv be modular_inverse_basic(divisor_leading, prime)
    
    While List.length(remainder) > divisor_degree:
        Let remainder_degree be List.length(remainder) - 1
        While remainder_degree > 0 && List.get(remainder, remainder_degree) == 0:
            Set remainder_degree to remainder_degree - 1
        
        If remainder_degree < divisor_degree:
            Break
        
        Let remainder_leading be List.get(remainder, remainder_degree)
        Let quotient_coeff be modular_multiply_basic(remainder_leading, divisor_leading_inv, prime)
        Let power_diff be remainder_degree - divisor_degree
        
        Note: Subtract quotient_coeff * x^power_diff * divisor from remainder
        Let i be 0
        While i <= divisor_degree:
            Let divisor_coeff be List.get(divisor, i)
            Let subtract_coeff be modular_multiply_basic(quotient_coeff, divisor_coeff, prime)
            Let remainder_idx be i + power_diff
            
            If remainder_idx < List.length(remainder):
                Let current_coeff be List.get(remainder, remainder_idx)
                Let new_coeff be modular_add_basic(current_coeff, prime - subtract_coeff, prime)
                Set remainder to List.set(remainder, remainder_idx, new_coeff)
            
            Set i to i + 1
        
        Note: Remove leading zeros
        While List.length(remainder) > 1 && List.get(remainder, List.length(remainder) - 1) == 0:
            Let new_remainder be []
            Let j be 0
            While j < List.length(remainder) - 1:
                Set new_remainder to List.append(new_remainder, List.get(remainder, j))
                Set j to j + 1
            Set remainder to new_remainder
    
    If List.length(remainder) == 0:
        Return [0]
    
    Return remainder

Process called "polynomial_divide_finite_field" that takes dividend as List[Integer], divisor as List[Integer], prime as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Compute quotient of polynomial division over F_p
    
    If List.length(divisor) == 0 || (List.length(divisor) == 1 && List.get(divisor, 0) == 0):
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Division by zero polynomial"
    
    Let quotient be []
    Let remainder be dividend
    Let divisor_degree be List.length(divisor) - 1
    While divisor_degree > 0 && List.get(divisor, divisor_degree) == 0:
        Set divisor_degree to divisor_degree - 1
    
    If divisor_degree < 0:
        Return [0]
    
    Let divisor_leading be List.get(divisor, divisor_degree)
    Let divisor_leading_inv be modular_inverse_basic(divisor_leading, prime)
    
    While List.length(remainder) > divisor_degree:
        Let remainder_degree be List.length(remainder) - 1
        While remainder_degree > 0 && List.get(remainder, remainder_degree) == 0:
            Set remainder_degree to remainder_degree - 1
        
        If remainder_degree < divisor_degree:
            Break
        
        Let remainder_leading be List.get(remainder, remainder_degree)
        Let quotient_coeff be modular_multiply_basic(remainder_leading, divisor_leading_inv, prime)
        Let power_diff be remainder_degree - divisor_degree
        
        Note: Extend quotient if necessary
        While List.length(quotient) <= power_diff:
            Set quotient to List.append(quotient, 0)
        
        Set quotient to List.set(quotient, power_diff, quotient_coeff)
        
        Note: Subtract quotient_coeff * x^power_diff * divisor from remainder
        Let i be 0
        While i <= divisor_degree:
            Let divisor_coeff be List.get(divisor, i)
            Let subtract_coeff be modular_multiply_basic(quotient_coeff, divisor_coeff, prime)
            Let remainder_idx be i + power_diff
            
            If remainder_idx < List.length(remainder):
                Let current_coeff be List.get(remainder, remainder_idx)
                Let new_coeff be modular_add_basic(current_coeff, prime - subtract_coeff, prime)
                Set remainder to List.set(remainder, remainder_idx, new_coeff)
            
            Set i to i + 1
        
        Note: Remove leading zeros from remainder
        While List.length(remainder) > 1 && List.get(remainder, List.length(remainder) - 1) == 0:
            Let new_remainder be []
            Let j be 0
            While j < List.length(remainder) - 1:
                Set new_remainder to List.append(new_remainder, List.get(remainder, j))
                Set j to j + 1
            Set remainder to new_remainder
    
    If List.length(quotient) == 0:
        Return [0]
    
    Return quotient

Process called "polynomial_multiply_mod_finite_field" that takes poly1 as List[Integer], poly2 as List[Integer], modulus_poly as List[Integer], prime as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Multiply two polynomials and reduce modulo another polynomial over F_p
    
    If List.length(poly1) == 0 || List.length(poly2) == 0:
        Return [0]
    
    Note: First multiply polynomials normally
    Let deg1 be List.length(poly1) - 1
    Let deg2 be List.length(poly2) - 1
    Let product_degree be deg1 + deg2
    
    Let product be []
    Let prod_i be 0
    While prod_i <= product_degree:
        Set product to List.append(product, 0)
        Set prod_i to prod_i + 1
    
    Let i1 be 0
    While i1 < List.length(poly1):
        Let coeff1 be List.get(poly1, i1)
        Let i2 be 0
        
        While i2 < List.length(poly2):
            Let coeff2 be List.get(poly2, i2)
            Let mult_result be modular_multiply_basic(coeff1, coeff2, prime)
            Let result_idx be i1 + i2
            Let current_coeff be List.get(product, result_idx)
            Let new_coeff be modular_add_basic(current_coeff, mult_result, prime)
            Set product to List.set(product, result_idx, new_coeff)
            Set i2 to i2 + 1
        
        Set i1 to i1 + 1
    
    Note: Now reduce modulo modulus_poly
    Return polynomial_remainder_finite_field(product, modulus_poly, prime)

Process called "polynomials_equal" that takes poly1 as List[Integer], poly2 as List[Integer] returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if two polynomials are equal (ignoring leading zeros)
    
    Note: Remove leading zeros from both polynomials
    Let norm1 be poly1
    While List.length(norm1) > 1 && List.get(norm1, List.length(norm1) - 1) == 0:
        Let temp1 be []
        Let i be 0
        While i < List.length(norm1) - 1:
            Set temp1 to List.append(temp1, List.get(norm1, i))
            Set i to i + 1
        Set norm1 to temp1
    
    Let norm2 be poly2  
    While List.length(norm2) > 1 && List.get(norm2, List.length(norm2) - 1) == 0:
        Let temp2 be []
        Let j be 0
        While j < List.length(norm2) - 1:
            Set temp2 to List.append(temp2, List.get(norm2, j))
            Set j to j + 1
        Set norm2 to temp2
    
    If List.length(norm1) != List.length(norm2):
        Return false
    
    Let k be 0
    While k < List.length(norm1):
        If List.get(norm1, k) != List.get(norm2, k):
            Return false
        Set k to k + 1
    
    Return true

Process called "modular_add_basic" that takes a as Integer, b as Integer, modulus as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Basic modular addition for polynomial coefficient arithmetic
    Let result be (a + b) % modulus
    If result < 0:
        Set result to result + modulus
    Return result

Process called "modular_multiply_basic" that takes a as Integer, b as Integer, modulus as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Basic modular multiplication for polynomial coefficient arithmetic
    Let result be (a * b) % modulus
    If result < 0:
        Set result to result + modulus
    Return result

Process called "modular_inverse_basic" that takes a as Integer, modulus as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Basic modular inverse using extended Euclidean algorithm for polynomial arithmetic
    
    Let normalized_a be a % modulus
    If normalized_a < 0:
        Set normalized_a to normalized_a + modulus
    
    If normalized_a == 0:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Cannot compute inverse of 0"
    
    Let old_r be modulus
    Let r be normalized_a
    Let old_s be 0
    Let s be 1
    
    While r != 0:
        Let quotient be old_r / r
        
        Let temp_r be r
        Set r to old_r - quotient * r
        Set old_r to temp_r
        
        Let temp_s be s
        Set s to old_s - quotient * s
        Set old_s to temp_s
    
    If old_r != 1:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Modular inverse does not exist"
    
    Let result be old_s % modulus
    If result < 0:
        Set result to result + modulus
    
    Return result